# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: polish-language
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:polish-language/1921-upper-silesia-plebiscite] The **Upper Silesia plebiscite** was a plebiscite mandated by the Versailles Treaty and carried out on 20 March 1921 to determine ownership of the province of Upper Silesia between Weimar Germany and the Second Polish Republic.
[src:polish-language/1921-upper-silesia-plebiscite] The region was ethnically mixed with both Germans and Poles.
[src:polish-language/1921-upper-silesia-plebiscite] According to prewar statistics, ethnic Poles formed 60 percent of the population.
[src:polish-language/1921-upper-silesia-plebiscite] Under the previous rule by the German Empire, Poles claimed they had faced discrimination and had been effectively second-class citizens.
[src:polish-language/1921-upper-silesia-plebiscite] The period of the plebiscite campaign and the Allied occupation was marked by violence.
[src:polish-language/1921-upper-silesia-plebiscite] Three Polish uprisings occurred, and German volunteer paramilitary units came to the region.
[src:polish-language/1921-upper-silesia-plebiscite] The area was policed by French, British and Italian troops and overseen by an Interallied Commission.
[src:polish-language/1921-upper-silesia-plebiscite] The Allies planned a partition of the region, but a Polish insurgency took control of over half the area.
[src:polish-language/1921-upper-silesia-plebiscite] The Germans responded with the Freikorps, volunteer paramilitary units from all over Germany that fought the Polish units.
[src:polish-language/1921-upper-silesia-plebiscite] The Freikorps from all over Germany participated in the plebiscite, as well as other bussed-in Germans.
[src:polish-language/1921-upper-silesia-plebiscite] In the end, after renewed Allied military intervention, the final position of the opposing forces became, roughly, the new border.
[src:polish-language/1921-upper-silesia-plebiscite] The decision was handed over to the League of Nations, which confirmed the border, and Poland received roughly one third of the plebiscite zone by area, including the greater part of the industrial region.
[src:polish-language/1921-upper-silesia-plebiscite] After the referendum, a conference of ambassadors in Paris on 20 October 1921 decided to divide the region.
[src:polish-language/1921-upper-silesia-plebiscite] Consequently, the German-Polish Accord on East Silesia (Geneva Convention), a minority treaty, was concluded on 15 May 1922 and dealt with the constitutional and legal future of Upper Silesia, which had partly become Polish territory.
[src:polish-language/1921-upper-silesia-plebiscite] The earliest exact census figures on ethnolinguistic or national structure (Nationalverschiedenheit) of the Prussian part of Upper Silesia, come from 1819.
[src:polish-language/1921-upper-silesia-plebiscite] Polish immigration from Galicia, Congress Poland and Prussian provinces into Upper Silesia during the 19th century was a major factor in their increasing numbers.
[src:polish-language/1921-upper-silesia-plebiscite] The last Prussian general census figures available are from 1910 (if not including the 1911 census of school children – Sprachzählung unter den Schulkindern – which revealed a higher percent of Polish-speakers among school children than the 1910 census among the general populace).
[src:polish-language/1921-upper-silesia-plebiscite] Figures (**Table 1.**) show that large demographic changes took place between 1819 and 1910, with the region's total population quadrupling, the percent of Germans increasing significantly, while Polish-speakers maintained their steady increasing numbers.
[src:polish-language/1921-upper-silesia-plebiscite] Also the total land area in which Polish was spoken, as well as the land area in which it was spoken, declined between 1790 and 1890.
[src:polish-language/1921-upper-silesia-plebiscite] Polish authors before 1918 estimated the number of Poles in Prussian Upper Silesia as slightly higher than according to official German censuses.
[src:polish-language/1921-upper-silesia-plebiscite] The three western districts of Falkenberg (Niemodlin), Grottkau (Grodków) and Neisse (Nysa), though part of Regierungsbezirk Oppeln, were not included in the plebiscite area, as they were almost entirely populated by Germans.
[src:polish-language/1921-upper-silesia-plebiscite] The Paris Peace Conference at the end of the First World War placed some formerly German territory in neighbouring countries, some of which had not existed before the war.
[src:polish-language/1921-upper-silesia-plebiscite] In the case of the new Second Polish Republic, the Treaty of Versailles established some 54,000 square kilometrs of formerly-German territory as part of the newly independent Poland.
[src:polish-language/1921-upper-silesia-plebiscite] Many of these areas were ethnically mixed.
[src:polish-language/1921-upper-silesia-plebiscite] In three of the ethnically mixed areas on the new German-Polish border, however, the Allied leaders provided for border plebiscites or referendums.
[src:polish-language/1921-upper-silesia-plebiscite] The areas would be occupied by Allied forces and governed to some degree by Allied commissions.
[src:polish-language/1921-upper-silesia-plebiscite] The most significant of those plebiscites was the one in Upper Silesia since the region was a principal industrial centre.
[src:polish-language/1921-upper-silesia-plebiscite] The most important economic asset was the enormous coal-mining industry and its ancillary businesses, but the area yielded iron, zinc, and lead.
[src:polish-language/1921-upper-silesia-plebiscite] The "Industrial Triangle", on the eastern side of the plebiscite zone, between the cities of Beuthen (Bytom), Kattowitz (Katowice), and Gleiwitz (Gliwice) was the heart of this large industrial complex.
[src:polish-language/1921-upper-silesia-plebiscite] The Upper Silesia plebiscite was therefore a plebiscite for self-determination of Upper Silesia required by the Treaty of Versailles.
[src:polish-language/1921-upper-silesia-plebiscite] Both Germany and Poland valued the region not only for reasons of national feeling but also for its economic importance.
[src:polish-language/1921-upper-silesia-plebiscite] The area was occupied by British, French, and Italian forces, and an Interallied Committee headed by a French general, Henri Le Rond.
[src:polish-language/1921-upper-silesia-plebiscite] The plebiscite was set for 20 March 1921.
[src:polish-language/1921-upper-silesia-plebiscite] Both Poles and Germans were allowed to organize campaigns.
[src:polish-language/1921-upper-silesia-plebiscite] Each side developed secret paramilitary forces, which were financed from the opposing capitals: Warsaw and Berlin.
[src:polish-language/1921-upper-silesia-plebiscite] The major figure of the campaign was Wojciech Korfanty, a pro-Polish politician.
[src:polish-language/1921-upper-silesia-plebiscite] The Poles carried out uprisings during the campaign in August 1919 and August 1920.
[src:polish-language/1921-upper-silesia-plebiscite] The Allies restored order in each case, but the Polish insurrectionists clashed with German "volunteers", the Freikorps.
[src:polish-language/1921-upper-silesia-plebiscite] There were 1,186,758 votes cast in an area inhabited by 2,073,663 people.
[src:polish-language/1921-upper-silesia-plebiscite] They resulted in 717,122 votes being cast for Germany and 483,514 for Poland.
[src:polish-language/1921-upper-silesia-plebiscite] The towns and most of the villages in the plebiscite territory had German majorities.
[src:polish-language/1921-upper-silesia-plebiscite] Many country communes of Upper Silesia had Polish majorities.
[src:polish-language/1921-upper-silesia-plebiscite] Overall, however, the Germans won the vote by a measure of 59.4% to 40.6%.
[src:polish-language/1921-upper-silesia-plebiscite] The Interallied Commission deliberated, but the British proposed a more easterly border than the French, which would have given much less of the Industrial Triangle to Poland.
[src:polish-language/1921-upper-silesia-plebiscite] In late April 1921, when pro-Polish forces began to fear that the region would be partitioned according to the British plan, elements on the Polish side announced a popular uprising.
[src:polish-language/1921-upper-silesia-plebiscite] Korfanty was the leading figure of the uprising, but he had much support in Upper Silesia and from the Polish government, in Warsaw.
[src:polish-language/1921-upper-silesia-plebiscite] Korfanty called for a popular armed uprising, whose aim was to maximize the territory that Poland would receive in the partition.
[src:polish-language/1921-upper-silesia-plebiscite] German volunteers rushed to meet this uprising, and large-scale fighting took place in the late spring and early summer of 1921.
[src:polish-language/1921-upper-silesia-plebiscite] German-speaking spokesmen and German officials complained that the French units of the Upper Silesian army of occupation supported the insurrection by refusing to put down violent activities or to restore order.
[src:polish-language/1921-upper-silesia-plebiscite] Twelve days after the start of the uprising, Korfanty offered to take his Upper Silesian forces behind a line of demarcation if the released territory was occupied not by German forces but by Allied troops.
[src:polish-language/1921-upper-silesia-plebiscite] On 1 July, British troops returned to Upper Silesia to help French forces occupy this area.
[src:polish-language/1921-upper-silesia-plebiscite] Simultaneously with those events, the Interallied Commission pronounced a general amnesty for the illegal actions committed during the recent violence except for acts of revenge and cruelty.
[src:polish-language/1921-upper-silesia-plebiscite] The German defence force was finally withdrawn.
[src:polish-language/1921-upper-silesia-plebiscite] Because the Allied Supreme Council was unable to come to an agreement on the partition of the Upper Silesian territory on the basis of the confusing plebiscite results, a solution was found by turning the question over to the Council of the League of Nations.
[src:polish-language/1921-upper-silesia-plebiscite] Agreements between the Germans and Poles in Upper Silesia and appeals issued by both sides, as well as the dispatch of six battalions of Allied troops and the disbandment of the local guards, contributed markedly to the pacification of the district.
[src:polish-language/1921-upper-silesia-plebiscite] The German and Polish governments, under a League of Nations recommendation, agreed to enforce protections of minority interests that would last for 15 years.
[src:polish-language/1921-upper-silesia-plebiscite] Special measures were threatened in case either state refused to participate in the drawing up of such regulations or to accept them subsequently.
[src:polish-language/1921-upper-silesia-plebiscite] In the event, the German minority remaining on the Polish side of the border suffered considerable discrimination in the subsequent decades.
[src:polish-language/1921-upper-silesia-plebiscite] The Polish government, convinced by the economic and political power of the region and by the autonomist movement of the plebiscite campaign, decided to give Upper Silesia considerable autonomy, with a Silesian Parliament as a legislature and the Silesian Voivodship Council as the executive body.
[src:polish-language/1921-upper-silesia-plebiscite] On the German side the new Prussian province of Upper Silesia (*Oberschlesien*) with regional government in Oppeln was formed, likewise with special autonomy.
[src:polish-language/1921-upper-silesia-plebiscite] According to Article 88 of the Treaty of Versailles all inhabitants of the plebiscite district older than 20 years of age and those who had "been expelled by the German authorities and have not retained their domicile there" were entitled to return to vote.
[src:polish-language/1921-upper-silesia-plebiscite] That stipulation of the Treaty of Versailles allowed the participation of thousands of Upper Silesian migrant workers from western Germany (Ruhrpolen).
[src:polish-language/1921-upper-silesia-plebiscite] Hugo Service regards the transport of these eligible voters to Silesia, organized by German authorities, "a cynical act aimed at boosting the German vote" and as one of the reasons for the overall result.
[src:polish-language/1921-upper-silesia-plebiscite] As Service writes, although almost 60% of Upper Silesians voted for their region to remain part of Germany, it would be dubious to claim that most of them were ethnically German or regarded themselves as Germans.
[src:polish-language/1921-upper-silesia-plebiscite] Voting for Germany in the 1921 vote and regarding oneself as German were two different things.
[src:polish-language/1921-upper-silesia-plebiscite] People had diverse, often very pragmatic reasons for voting for Germany, which usually had little to do with regarding themselves as having a German ethnonational identity.
[src:polish-language/1921-upper-silesia-plebiscite] According to Robert Machray, a British international observer, 192,408 of all plebiscite voters were migrants and made up 16% of the total electorate.
[src:polish-language/1921-upper-silesia-plebiscite] There were cases of votes being cast in the name of already deceased persons who died outside of Upper Silesia, and since their deaths were registered "in comparatively inaccessible German registration departments in Central Germany", it was often difficult to detect voter fraud.
[src:polish-language/1921-upper-silesia-plebiscite] The Polish population of Silesia overwhelmingly consisted of poor workers and small farmers, who owned no real property and were highly dependent on the German authorities to provide appropriate infrastructure.
[src:polish-language/1921-upper-silesia-plebiscite] All offices and industries were controlled by the German population, who exerted an overwhelming pressure on Poles to vote for Germany, and they "frequently exceeded their lawful powers and supported many forms of anti-Polish activities".
[src:polish-language/1921-upper-silesia-plebiscite] Demobilised German officers joined the Freikorps and terrorised the Polish population.
[src:polish-language/1921-upper-silesia-plebiscite] Machray states, "Upper Silesia was the scene of incessant confusion, sanguinary struggles with armed German attacks on Polish meetings and on the terrorized and defenceless Polish population, especially in the rural areas".
[src:polish-language/1921-upper-silesia-plebiscite] Emil Julius Gumbel investigated and condemned the cases of widespread intimidation and murders by Freikorps and Selbstschutz divisions and remarked that “a denunciation, a suspicion without foundation under the given circumstances, was sufficient.
[src:polish-language/1921-upper-silesia-plebiscite] The man concerned is fetched from his lodgings and instantly shot... all this only because the man was a Pole or was considered a Pole and worked for union with Poland”.
[src:polish-language/1921-upper-silesia-plebiscite] Machray concludes that given the aggressive anti-Polish campaign conducted by local authorities and German volunteers, "the results were far from being an objective reflection of the true desires of the oppressed people".
[src:polish-language/1921-upper-silesia-plebiscite] The constant ethnic tensions and attacks on Polish voters resulted in the Silesian Uprisings.
[src:polish-language/1921-upper-silesia-plebiscite] The following table compares the percentage of German-speakers (excluding bilinguals) as reported in the 1910 census in each district, with the pro-German vote share registered in the respective district.
[src:polish-language/1921-upper-silesia-plebiscite] In almost all districts, the percentage of pro-German votes exceeded the percentage of those who identified as German by almost 25% on average, which suggests that many non-Germans voted in favour of Germany.
[src:polish-language/1921-upper-silesia-plebiscite] In the 1921 plebiscite, 40.6% of eligible voters decided to secede from Germany and become Polish citizens.
[src:polish-language/1921-upper-silesia-plebiscite] In total, over 700 towns and villages voted to secede from Germany and become part of Poland, especially in the rural districts of Pszczyna, Rybnik, Tarnowskie Góry, Toszek-Gliwice, Strzelce Opolskie, Bytom, Katowice, Lubliniec, Zabrze, Racibórz, Olesno, Koźle and Opole.
[src:polish-language/2000-united-states-census] The **2000 United States census**, conducted by the Census Bureau, determined the resident population of the United States on April 1, 2000, to be 281,421,906, an increase of 13.2 percent over the 248,709,873 people enumerated during the 1990 census.
[src:polish-language/2000-united-states-census] This was the twenty-second federal census and was at the time the largest civilly administered peacetime effort in the United States.
[src:polish-language/2000-united-states-census] Approximately 16 percent of households received a "long form" of the 2000 census, which contained over 100 questions.
[src:polish-language/2000-united-states-census] It would be the last census to include the "long form", since subsequent censuses, starting with the 2010 census, would be "short form" only, with the more detailed questions being replaced by the new American Community Survey.
[src:polish-language/2000-united-states-census] Full documentation on the 2000 census, including census forms and a procedural history, is available from the Integrated Public Use Microdata Series.
[src:polish-language/2000-united-states-census] This was the first census in which a state—California—recorded a population of over 30 million, as well as the first in which two states—California and Texas—recorded populations of more than 20 million.
[src:polish-language/2000-united-states-census] Microdata from the 2000 census is freely available through the Integrated Public Use Microdata Series.
[src:polish-language/2000-united-states-census] Aggregate data for small areas, together with electronic boundary files, can be downloaded from the National Historical Geographic Information System.
[src:polish-language/2000-united-states-census] Personally identifiable information will be available in 2072.
[src:polish-language/2000-united-states-census] The U.S. resident population includes the total number of people in the 50 states and the District of Columbia.
[src:polish-language/2000-united-states-census] The Bureau also enumerated the residents of the U.S. territory of Puerto Rico; its population was 3,808,610, an 8.1% increase over the number from a decade earlier.
[src:polish-language/2000-united-states-census] Regionally, the South and West experienced the bulk of the nation's population increase: 14,790,890 and 10,411,850, respectively.
[src:polish-language/2000-united-states-census] This meant that the mean center of U.S. population moved to Phelps County, Missouri.
[src:polish-language/2000-united-states-census] The Northeastern United States grew by 2,785,149; the Midwest by 4,724,144.
[src:polish-language/2000-united-states-census] The results of the census are used to determine how many congressional districts each state is apportioned.
[src:polish-language/2000-united-states-census] Congress defines the formula, in accordance with Title 2 of the U.S.
[src:polish-language/2000-united-states-census] Code, to reapportion among the states the 435 seats in the United States House of Representatives.
[src:polish-language/2000-united-states-census] The apportionment population consists of the resident population of the fifty states, plus the overseas military and federal civilian employees and their dependents living with them who could be allocated to a state.
[src:polish-language/2000-united-states-census] Each member of the House represents a population of about 647,000.
[src:polish-language/2000-united-states-census] The populations of the District of Columbia and Puerto Rico are excluded from the apportionment population because they do not have voting seats in the U.
[src:polish-language/2000-united-states-census] Since the first census in 1790, the decennial count has been the basis for the United States representative form of government.
[src:polish-language/2000-united-states-census] Article I, Section II specifies that "The Number of Representatives shall not exceed one for every thirty Thousand, but each State shall have at Least one Representative." In 1790, each member of the House represented about 34,000 residents.
[src:polish-language/2000-united-states-census] Since then, the House more than quadrupled in size, and in 1911 the number of representatives was fixed at 435.
[src:polish-language/2000-united-states-census] Today, each member represents about 20 times as many constituents.
[src:polish-language/2000-united-states-census] In the years leading up to the 2000 census, there was substantial controversy over whether the Bureau should adjust census figures based on a follow-up survey, called the post-enumeration survey, of a sample of blocks.
[src:polish-language/2000-united-states-census] This recommendation was followed by the Secretary of Commerce (the official in charge of making the determination).
[src:polish-language/2000-united-states-census] After the census was tabulated, Utah challenged the results in two different ways.
[src:polish-language/2000-united-states-census] Utah was extremely close to gaining a fourth congressional seat, falling 857 people short, which in turn was allocated to North Carolina.
[src:polish-language/2000-united-states-census] The margin was later shortened to 80 people, after the federal government discovered that it overcounted the population of North Carolina by 2,673 residents.
[src:polish-language/2000-united-states-census] The Census Bureau counted members of the military and other federal civilian employees serving abroad as residents of their home state but did not count other people living outside the United States.
[src:polish-language/2000-united-states-census] Utah claimed that people traveling abroad as religious missionaries should be counted as residents and that the failure to do so imposed a burden on Mormon religious practice.
[src:polish-language/2000-united-states-census] Almost half of all Mormon missionaries, more than 11,000 people, were from Utah; only 102 came from North Carolina.
[src:polish-language/2000-united-states-census] If this policy were changed, then Utah would have received an additional seat instead of North Carolina.
[src:polish-language/2000-united-states-census] On November 26, 2002, the Supreme Court affirmed the lower court ruling that rejected Utah's efforts to have Mormon missionaries counted.
[src:polish-language/2000-united-states-census] The state of Utah then filed another lawsuit alleging that the statistical methods used in computing the state populations were improper and cost Utah the seat.
[src:polish-language/2000-united-states-census] The Bureau uses a method called imputation to assign a number of residents to addresses where residents cannot be reached after multiple efforts.
[src:polish-language/2000-united-states-census] While nationwide the imputation method added 0.4% to the population, the rate in Utah was 0.2%.
[src:polish-language/2000-united-states-census] The state challenged that the use of imputation violates the Census Act of 1957 and that it also fails the Constitution's requirement in Article I, Section 2 that an "actual enumeration" be used for apportionment.
[src:polish-language/2000-united-states-census] Evans*, made it to the Supreme Court, but Utah was again defeated.
[src:polish-language/2000-united-states-census] The census forms did not include any questions regarding sexual orientation, making it impossible to compile data comparing heterosexual and homosexual populations.
[src:polish-language/2000-united-states-census] However, two questions *were* asked that allowed same-sex partnerships to be counted.
[src:polish-language/2000-united-states-census] The questionnaires asked the sex of each person in a household and they asked what the relationship was between each of the members of the household.
[src:polish-language/2000-united-states-census] Respondents could check "Husband/wife" or "unmarried partner" or a number of other relationships.
[src:polish-language/2000-united-states-census] Responses were tabulated and the Census Bureau reported that there were more than 658,000 same-sex couples heading households in the United States.
[src:polish-language/2000-united-states-census] However, only about 25% of gay men and 40% of lesbians are in shared-household partnerships at any one time, according to non-census surveys.
[src:polish-language/2000-united-states-census] For every same-sex couple tallied in the census, there could be three to six more homosexual un-partnered individuals who would not be counted as gay.
[src:polish-language/2000-united-states-census] The census reported that same-sex male couples numbered 336,001 and female same-sex couples numbered 329,522.
[src:polish-language/2000-united-states-census] Extrapolating from those figures and the surveyed partnering habits of homosexuals, as many as 4.3 million homosexual adults could have been living in the U.S. in 2000.
[src:polish-language/2000-united-states-census] The exact number cannot be known because the census did not count them specifically.
[src:polish-language/2000-united-states-census] Bisexual and transgender populations were not counted, either, because there were no questions regarding this information.
[src:polish-language/2000-united-states-census] Also unavailable is the number of additional same-sex couples living under the same roof as the first, though this applies to additional heterosexual couples as well.
[src:polish-language/2000-united-states-census] The lack of accurate numbers makes it difficult for lawmakers who are considering legislation on hate crimes or social services for gay families with children.
[src:polish-language/2000-united-states-census] It also makes for less accuracy when predicting the fertility of a population.
[src:polish-language/2000-united-states-census] Another issue that concerned gay rights advocates involved the automatic changing of data during the tabulation process.
[src:polish-language/2000-united-states-census] This automatic software data compiling method, called *allocation*, was designed to counteract mistakes and discrepancies in returned questionnaires.
[src:polish-language/2000-united-states-census] Forms that were filled out by two same-sex persons who checked the "Husband/wife" relationship box were treated as a discrepancy.
[src:polish-language/2000-united-states-census] The Census Bureau explained that same-sex "Husband/wife" data samples were changed to "unmarried partner" by computer processing methods in 99% of the cases.
[src:polish-language/2000-united-states-census] In the remaining 1%, computer systems used one of two possibilities: a) one of the two listed sexes was changed, making the partnership appear heterosexual, or b) if the two partners were more than 15 years apart in age, they might have been reassigned into a familial parent/child relationship.
[src:polish-language/2000-united-states-census] The process of automatic reassignment of same-sex marriage data was initiated so that the Census Bureau would not contravene the Defense of Marriage Act passed in 1996.
[src:polish-language/2000-united-states-census] With allocation moving married same-sex couples to the unmarried partner category, social scientists lost information that could have been extracted relating to the social stability of a same-gender couple who identify themselves as married.
[src:polish-language/a] It is similar in shape to the Ancient Greek letter alpha, from which it derives.
[src:polish-language/a] The uppercase version consists of the two slanting sides of a triangle, crossed in the middle by a horizontal bar.
[src:polish-language/a] The lowercase version is often written in one of two forms: the double-storey |a| and single-storey |ɑ|.
[src:polish-language/a] The latter form is commonly used in handwriting and fonts based on it, especially fonts intended to be read by children, and is also found in italic type.
[src:polish-language/a] In English, the name of the letter is the *long A* sound, pronounced /ˈeɪ/.
[src:polish-language/a] Its name in most other languages matches the letter's pronunciation in open syllables.
[src:polish-language/a] The earliest known ancestor of A is *aleph*—the first letter of the Phoenician alphabet—where it represented a glottal stop [ʔ], as Phoenician only used consonantal letters.
[src:polish-language/a] In turn, the ancestor of aleph may have been a pictogram of an ox head in proto-Sinaitic script influenced by Egyptian hieroglyphs, styled as a triangular head with two horns extended.
[src:polish-language/a] When the ancient Greeks adopted the alphabet, they had no use for a letter representing a glottal stop—so they adapted the sign to represent the vowel /a/, calling the letter by the similar name *alpha*.
[src:polish-language/a] In the earliest Greek inscriptions dating to the 8th century BC following the Greek Dark Ages, the letter rests upon its side.
[src:polish-language/a] However, in the later Greek alphabet it generally resembles the modern capital form—though many local varieties can be distinguished by the shortening of one leg, or by the angle at which the cross line is set.
[src:polish-language/a] The Etruscans brought the Greek alphabet to the Italian Peninsula, and they left the form of alpha unchanged.
[src:polish-language/a] When the Romans adopted the Etruscan alphabet to write Latin, the resulting form used in the Latin script would come to be used to write many other languages, including English.
[src:polish-language/a] During Roman times, there were many variant forms of the letter A.
[src:polish-language/a] First was the monumental or lapidary style, which was used when inscribing on stone or other more permanent media.
[src:polish-language/a] There was also a cursive style used for everyday or utilitarian writing, which was done on more perishable surfaces.
[src:polish-language/a] Due to the perishable nature of these surfaces, there are not as many examples of this style as there are of the monumental, but there are still many surviving examples of different types of cursive, such as majuscule cursive, minuscule cursive, and semi-cursive minuscule.
[src:polish-language/a] Variants also existed that were intermediate between the monumental and cursive styles.
[src:polish-language/a] The known variants include the early semi-uncial (c.
[src:polish-language/a] 4th–8th centuries), and the late semi-uncial (c.
[src:polish-language/a] At the end of the Roman Empire (5th century CE), several variants of the cursive minuscule developed through Western Europe.
[src:polish-language/a] Among these were the semi-cursive minuscule of Italy, the Merovingian script in France, the Visigothic script in Spain, and the Insular or Anglo-Irish semi-uncial or Anglo-Saxon majuscule of Great Britain.
[src:polish-language/a] By the ninth century, the Caroline script, which was very similar to the present-day form, was the principal form used in book-making, before the advent of the printing press.
[src:polish-language/a] This form was derived through a combining of prior forms.
[src:polish-language/a] 15th-century Italy saw the formation of the two main variants that are known today.
[src:polish-language/a] These variants, the *Italic* and *Roman* forms, were derived from the Caroline Script version.
[src:polish-language/a] The Italic form ⟨ɑ⟩, also called *script a*, is often used in handwriting; it consists of a circle with a vertical stroke on its right.
[src:polish-language/a] In the hands of medieval Irish and English writers, this form gradually developed from a 5th-century form resembling the Greek letter tau ⟨τ⟩.
[src:polish-language/a] The Roman form ⟨a⟩ is found in most printed material, and consists of a small loop with an arc over it.
[src:polish-language/a] Both derive from the majuscule form ⟨A⟩.
[src:polish-language/a] In Greek handwriting, it was common to join the left leg and horizontal stroke into a single loop, as demonstrated by the uncial version shown.
[src:polish-language/a] Many fonts then made the right leg vertical.
[src:polish-language/a] In some of these, the serif that began the right leg stroke developed into an arc, resulting in the printed form, while in others it was dropped, resulting in the modern handwritten form.
[src:polish-language/a] Graphic designers refer to the *Italic* and *Roman* forms as *single-decker a* and *double decker a* respectively.
[src:polish-language/a] Italic type is commonly used to mark emphasis or more generally to distinguish one part of a text from the rest set in Roman type.
[src:polish-language/a] There are some other cases aside from italic type where *script a* ⟨ɑ⟩, also called *Latin alpha*, is used in contrast with Latin ⟨a⟩, such as in the International Phonetic Alphabet.
[src:polish-language/a] In English, ⟨a⟩ is the indefinite article (with the alternative form *an* when followed by a vowel).
[src:polish-language/a] The double ⟨aa⟩ sequence does not occur in native English words, but is found in some words derived from foreign languages such as *Aaron* and *aardvark*.
[src:polish-language/a] However, ⟨a⟩ occurs in many common digraphs, all with their own sound or sounds, particularly ⟨ai⟩, ⟨au⟩, ⟨aw⟩, ⟨ay⟩, ⟨ea⟩ and ⟨oa⟩.
[src:polish-language/a] In most languages that use the Latin alphabet, ⟨a⟩ denotes an open unrounded vowel, such as /a/, /ä/, or /ɑ/.
[src:polish-language/a] An exception is Saanich, in which ⟨a⟩—and the glyph ⟨Á⟩—stands for a close-mid front unrounded vowel /e/.
[src:polish-language/a] The Latin letters ⟨A⟩ and ⟨a⟩ have Unicode encodings U+0041 A LATIN CAPITAL LETTER A and U+0061 a LATIN SMALL LETTER A.
[src:polish-language/a] These are the same code points as those used in ASCII and ISO 8859.
[src:polish-language/a] There are also precomposed character encodings for ⟨A⟩ and ⟨a⟩ with diacritics, for most of those listed above; the remainder are produced using combining diacritics.
[src:polish-language/a] Variant forms of the letter have unique code points for specialist use: the alphanumeric symbols set in mathematics and science, Latin alpha in linguistics, and halfwidth and fullwidth forms for legacy CJK font compatibility.
[src:polish-language/a] The Cyrillic and Greek homoglyphs of the Latin ⟨A⟩ have separate encodings U+0410 А CYRILLIC CAPITAL LETTER A and U+0391 Α GREEK CAPITAL LETTER ALPHA.
[src:polish-language/acute-accent] The **acute accent** (´, ◌́) is a diacritic used in many modern written languages with alphabets based on the Latin, Cyrillic, and Greek scripts.
[src:polish-language/acute-accent] For the most commonly encountered uses of the accent in the Latin and Greek alphabets, precomposed characters are available.
[src:polish-language/acute-accent] An early precursor of the acute accent was the apex, used in Latin inscriptions to mark long vowels.
[src:polish-language/acute-accent] The acute accent was first used in French in 1530 by Geoffroy Tory, the royal printer.
[src:polish-language/acute-accent] The acute accent was first used in the polytonic orthography of Ancient Greek, where it indicated a syllable with a high pitch.
[src:polish-language/acute-accent] In Modern Greek, a stress accent has replaced the pitch accent, and the acute marks the stressed syllable of a word.
[src:polish-language/acute-accent] The Greek name of the accented syllable was and is ὀξεῖα (*oxeîa*, Modern Greek *oxía*) "sharp" or "high", which was calqued (loan-translated) into Latin as *acūta* "sharpened".
[src:polish-language/acute-accent] The acute accent marks the height of some stressed vowels in various Romance languages.
[src:polish-language/acute-accent] A graphically similar, but not identical, mark is indicative of a palatalized sound in several languages.
[src:polish-language/acute-accent] In Polish, such a mark is known as a ***kreska*** ("stroke") and is an integral part of several letters: four consonants and one vowel.
[src:polish-language/acute-accent] When appearing in consonants, it indicates palatalization, similar to the use of the *háček* in Czech and other Slavic languages (e.g.
[src:polish-language/acute-accent] However, in contrast to the *háček* which is usually used for postalveolar consonants, the *kreska* denotes alveolo-palatal consonants.
[src:polish-language/acute-accent] In traditional Polish typography, the *kreska* is more nearly vertical than the acute accent, and placed slightly right of center.
[src:polish-language/acute-accent] A similar rule applies to the Belarusian Latin alphabet *Łacinka*.
[src:polish-language/acute-accent] However, for computer use, Unicode conflates the codepoints for these letters with those of the accented Latin letters of similar appearance.
[src:polish-language/acute-accent] In Serbo-Croatian, as in Polish, the letter ⟨ć⟩ is used to represent a voiceless alveolo-palatal affricate /t͡ɕ/.
[src:polish-language/acute-accent] In the romanization of Macedonian, ⟨ǵ⟩ and ⟨ḱ⟩ represent the Cyrillic letters ⟨ѓ⟩ (Gje) and ⟨ќ⟩ (Kje), which stand for palatal or alveolo-palatal consonants, though ⟨gj⟩ and ⟨kj⟩ (or ⟨đ⟩ and ⟨ć⟩) are more commonly used for this purpose.
[src:polish-language/acute-accent] The same two letters are used to transcribe the postulated Proto-Indo-European phonemes /ɡʲ/ and /kʲ/.
[src:polish-language/acute-accent] Sorbian uses the acute for palatalization as in Polish: ⟨ć dź ń⟩.
[src:polish-language/acute-accent] Lower Sorbian also uses ⟨ŕ ś ź⟩, and Lower Sorbian previously used ⟨ḿ ṕ ẃ⟩ and ⟨b́ f́⟩, also written as ⟨b' f'⟩; these are now spelt as ⟨mj pj wj⟩ and ⟨bj fj⟩.
[src:polish-language/acute-accent] In the *Quốc Ngữ* system for Vietnamese, the Yale romanization for Cantonese, the Pinyin romanization for Mandarin Chinese, and the Bopomofo semi-syllabary, the acute accent indicates a rising tone.
[src:polish-language/acute-accent] In Mandarin, the alternative to the acute accent is the number 2 after the syllable: *lái* = *lai2*.
[src:polish-language/acute-accent] In Cantonese Yale, the acute accent is either tone 2, or tone 5 if the vowel(s) are followed by 'h' (if the number form is used, 'h' is omitted): *má* = *ma2*, *máh* = *ma5*.
[src:polish-language/acute-accent] In African languages and Athabaskan languages, it frequently marks a high tone, e.g., Yoruba *apá* 'arm', Nobiin *féntí* 'sweet date', Koti *kaláwa* 'boat', Navajo *tʼáá* 'just'.
[src:polish-language/acute-accent] Also the Uto-Aztecan language Hopi can use the acute accent to mark a higher tone.
[src:polish-language/acute-accent] The acute accent is used in Serbo-Croatian dictionaries and linguistic publications to indicate a high-rising accent.
[src:polish-language/acute-accent] Retention of the accent is common only in the French ending *é* or *ée*, as in these examples, where its absence would tend to suggest a different pronunciation.
[src:polish-language/acute-accent] Thus the French word *résumé* is commonly seen in English as *resumé*, with only one accent (but also with both or none).
[src:polish-language/acute-accent] For foreign terms used in English that have not been assimilated into English or are not in general English usage, italics are generally used with the appropriate accents: for example, *coup d'état*, *pièce de résistance*, *crème brûlée* and *ancien régime*.
[src:polish-language/acute-accent] The layout of some European PC keyboards, combined with problematic keyboard-driver semantics, causes some users to use an acute accent or a grave accent instead of an apostrophe when typing in English (e.g. typing John´s or John`s instead of John's).
[src:polish-language/acute-accent] Western typographic and calligraphic traditions generally design the acute accent as going from top to bottom.
[src:polish-language/acute-accent] French even has the definition of acute is the accent *«qui va de droite à gauche»* (English: "which goes from right to left"), meaning that it descends from top right to lower left.
[src:polish-language/acute-accent] In Polish, the *kreska* diacritic is used instead, which usually has a different shape and style compared to other European languages.
[src:polish-language/acute-accent] It features a more vertical steep form and is moved more to the right side of center line than acute.
[src:polish-language/acute-accent] As Unicode does not differentiate the *kreska* from the acute, letters from Western (computer) fonts and Polish fonts have had to share the same set of code points, which make designing the conflicting character (i.e.
[src:polish-language/acute-accent] OpenType tried to solve this problem by giving language-sensitive glyph substitution to designers, such that the font would automatically switch between Western ⟨ó⟩ and Polish ⟨ó⟩ based on language settings.
[src:polish-language/acute-accent] New computer fonts are sensitive to this issue and their design for the diacritics tends toward a more "universal design" so that there will be less need for localization, for example Roboto and Noto typefaces.
[src:polish-language/acute-accent] Pinyin uses the acute accent to mark the second tone (rising or high-rising tone), which indicates a tone rising from low to high, causing the writing stroke of acute accent to go from lower left to top right.
[src:polish-language/acute-accent] This contradicts the Western typographic tradition which makes designing the acute accent in Chinese typefaces a problem.
[src:polish-language/acute-accent] Designers approach this problem in 3 ways: either keep the original Western form of going top right (thicker) to bottom left (thinner) (e.g.
[src:polish-language/acute-accent] Arial/Times New Roman), flip the stroke to go from bottom left (thicker) to top right (thinner) (e.g.
[src:polish-language/acute-accent] Adobe HeiTi Std/SimSun), or just make the accents without stroke variation (e.g.
[src:polish-language/acute-accent] Unicode encodes a number of cases of "letter with acute accent" as precomposed characters and these are displayed below.
[src:polish-language/acute-accent] Computer keyboards sold in many countries have an AltGr ('alternate graphic') key (or Option key) which adds a third and (with the Shift key) fourth effect to most keys.
[src:polish-language/acute-accent] Thus AltGr+a produces á and AltGr+A produces Á.
[src:polish-language/acute-accent] (Most languages require diacritics ('accents') and thus an 'extended' or national keyboard mapping is required.
[src:polish-language/acute-accent] Because keyboards have only a limited number of keys, US standard keyboards do not have keys for accented characters.
[src:polish-language/acute-accent] An alternative method is the 'dead key', a key that modifies the meaning of the next key press.
[src:polish-language/acute-accent] This method was used with typewriters where, when the typist typed an accent, the carriage did not move as usual with the effect that the next letter would be written on the same place on the paper.
[src:polish-language/acute-accent] An appropriate keyboard mapping (such as US-International) provides this function via the right-hand Alt key.
[src:polish-language/acute-accent] Thus RightAlt+' (apostrophe) is a dead key so appears to have no effect until the next key is pressed, when it adds the desired acute accent.
[src:polish-language/adam-asnyk] Born in Kalisz to a szlachta family, he was educated to become an heir of his family's estate.
[src:polish-language/adam-asnyk] As such he received education at the Institute of Agriculture and Forestry in Marymont and then the Medical Surgeon School in Warsaw.
[src:polish-language/adam-asnyk] He continued his studies abroad in Breslau, Paris, Heidelberg and surprisingly in Sofia for a brief time.
[src:polish-language/adam-asnyk] In 1862, he returned to Congress Poland and took part in the January Uprising against Russian rule.
[src:polish-language/adam-asnyk] Because of that he had to flee his country and settled in Heidelberg, where in 1866 he received a doctorate of philosophy.
[src:polish-language/adam-asnyk] Soon afterwards he returned to Poland and settled in the Austrian-held part of the country, initially in Lwów and then in Kraków.
[src:polish-language/adam-asnyk] In 1875, Asnyk married Zofia née Kaczorowska, with whom he had a son, Włodzimierz, and around that time started his career as a journalist.
[src:polish-language/adam-asnyk] An editor of a Kraków-based *Reforma* daily, in 1884 he was also chosen to the city council of Kraków.
[src:polish-language/adam-asnyk] Five years later he was elected to the Diet of Galicia and Lodomeria.
[src:polish-language/adam-asnyk] Around that time he became one of the most prominent men of culture in partitioned Poland.
[src:polish-language/adam-asnyk] Among his initiatives was the creation of the Society of Popular Schools and bringing the ashes of Adam Mickiewicz to Poland.
[src:polish-language/adam-asnyk] He was also among the first members of the Tatra Society.
[src:polish-language/adam-asnyk] He died on 2 August 1897 in Kraków and was buried at the Skałka church, a burial place for some of the most distinguished Poles, particularly those who lived in Kraków.
[src:polish-language/adam-asnyk] Some of his poems, for example *Ulewa* (*The Heavy Rain*) or *Daremne żale* (*The Vain regrets*), are among the best examples of iambic metre in all of Polish literature.
[src:polish-language/adam-asnyk] He also used sophisticated strophes, for instance ottava rima.
[src:polish-language/adam-asnyk] The poem *Wśród przełomu* (*At the breakthrough*) is perhaps the first use of rhyme royal in original Polish poetry.
[src:polish-language/adam-asnyk] His versification was often discussed by prominent Polish scholars, among others by Maria Dłuska and Lucylla Pszczołowska.
[src:polish-language/adam-mickiewicz-institute] The **Adam Mickiewicz Institute** (Polish: *Instytut Adama Mickiewicza*) is a government-sponsored organization funded by Poland's Ministry of Culture and National Heritage, and headquartered at 25 Mokotowska Street (the Sugar Palace) in Warsaw.
[src:polish-language/adam-mickiewicz-institute] Named after Polish national poet Adam Mickiewicz, its goal is to promote the Polish language and Polish culture abroad.
[src:polish-language/adam-mickiewicz-institute] Since 2001, the institute operates Culture.pl, a web portal documenting various aspects of Polish culture.
[src:polish-language/adam-mickiewicz-institute] As of 2025, Culture.pl is available in 8 languages including Polish and English.
[src:polish-language/adam-mickiewicz-institute] While the Adam Mickiewicz Institute frequently collaborates with the Polish Cultural Institutes, each institution is independent of the other and is sponsored by a different Polish government ministry.
[src:polish-language/adam-mickiewicz] He is known chiefly for the poetic drama *Dziady* (*Forefathers' Eve*) and the national epic poem *Pan Tadeusz*.
[src:polish-language/adam-mickiewicz] His other influential works include *Konrad Wallenrod* and *Grażyna*.
[src:polish-language/adam-mickiewicz] All these served as inspiration for uprisings against the three imperial powers that had partitioned the Polish–Lithuanian Commonwealth out of existence.
[src:polish-language/adam-mickiewicz] His works also promoted the Lithuanian National Revival; the opening of Lithuania's national anthem, *Tautiška giesmė* (1898), is a paraphrase of the opening of *Pan Tadeusz*.
[src:polish-language/adam-mickiewicz] Mickiewicz was born in the Russian-partitioned territories of the former Grand Duchy of Lithuania, which had been part of the Polish–Lithuanian Commonwealth, and was active in the struggle to win independence for his home region.
[src:polish-language/adam-mickiewicz] After, as a consequence, spending five years exiled to central Russia, in 1829 he succeeded in leaving the Russian Empire and, like many of his compatriots, lived out the rest of his life abroad.
[src:polish-language/adam-mickiewicz] He settled first in Rome, then in Paris, where for a little over three years he lectured on Slavic literature at the Collège de France.
[src:polish-language/adam-mickiewicz] However, his increasing involvement with the religious mysticism of Andrzej Towiański brought him into conflict with the French authorities and the Catholic Church, and he eventually lost the post.
[src:polish-language/adam-mickiewicz] In 1849 Mickiewicz founded the French-language newspaper *La Tribune des Peuples*, writing in support of democracy, socialism and national liberation.
[src:polish-language/adam-mickiewicz] He was an activist, striving for a democratic and independent Poland.
[src:polish-language/adam-mickiewicz] He died, probably of cholera, at Istanbul in the Ottoman Empire, where he had gone to help organize Polish and Jewish forces to fight Russia in the Crimean War.
[src:polish-language/adam-mickiewicz] In 1894, his remains were repatriated from Montmorency, Val-d'Oise, in France, to Wawel Cathedral in Kraków, Poland.
[src:polish-language/adam-mickiewicz] Adam Mickiewicz was born on 24 December 1798, either at his paternal uncle's estate in Zavosse (Polish: *Zaosie*) near Navahrudak (Polish: *Nowogródek*) or in Navahrudak itself in what was then part of the Russian Empire and is now Belarus.
[src:polish-language/adam-mickiewicz] The region was on the periphery of Lithuania proper and had been part of the Grand Duchy of Lithuania until the Third Partition of the Polish–Lithuanian Commonwealth (1795).
[src:polish-language/adam-mickiewicz] Its upper class, including Mickiewicz's family, were either Polish or Polonized.
[src:polish-language/adam-mickiewicz] The poet's father, Mikołaj Mickiewicz, a lawyer, was a member of the Polish nobility (*szlachta*) and bore the hereditary Poraj coat-of-arms; Adam's mother was Barbara Mickiewicz, *née* Majewska.
[src:polish-language/adam-mickiewicz] Adam was the second-born son in the family.
[src:polish-language/adam-mickiewicz] Mickiewicz spent his childhood in Navahrudak, initially taught by his mother and private tutors.
[src:polish-language/adam-mickiewicz] From 1807 to 1815 he attended a Dominican school following a curriculum that had been designed by the now-defunct Polish Commission of National Education, which had been the world's first ministry of education.
[src:polish-language/adam-mickiewicz] He was a mediocre student, although active in games, theatricals, and the like.
[src:polish-language/adam-mickiewicz] In September 1815, Mickiewicz enrolled at the Imperial University of Vilnius, studying to be a teacher.
[src:polish-language/adam-mickiewicz] After graduating, under the terms of his government scholarship, he taught secondary school at Kaunas from 1819 to 1823.
[src:polish-language/adam-mickiewicz] In 1818, in the Polish-language *Tygodnik Wileński* (Wilno Weekly), he published his first poem, *Zima miejska* (*City Winter*).
[src:polish-language/adam-mickiewicz] By 1820 he had already finished another major romantic poem, *Oda do młodości* (*Ode to Youth*), but it was considered to be too patriotic and revolutionary for publication and would not appear officially for many years.
[src:polish-language/adam-mickiewicz] About the summer of 1820, Mickiewicz met the love of his life, Maryla Wereszczakówna.
[src:polish-language/adam-mickiewicz] They were unable to marry due to his family's poverty and relatively low social status; in addition, she was already engaged to Count Wawrzyniec Puttkamer, whom she would marry in 1821.
[src:polish-language/adam-mickiewicz] In 1817, while still a student, Mickiewicz, Tomasz Zan and other friends had created a secret organization, the Philomaths.
[src:polish-language/adam-mickiewicz] The group focused on self-education but had ties to a more radical, clearly pro-Polish-independence student group, the Filaret Association.
[src:polish-language/adam-mickiewicz] After investigation into his political activities, specifically his membership in the Philomaths, in 1824 Mickiewicz was banished to central Russia.
[src:polish-language/adam-mickiewicz] Within a few hours of receiving the decree on 22 October 1824, he penned a poem into an album belonging to Salomea Bécu, the mother of Juliusz Słowacki.
[src:polish-language/adam-mickiewicz] (In 1975 this poem was set to music in Polish and Russian by Soviet composer David Tukhmanov.) Mickiewicz crossed the border into Russia about 11 November 1824, arriving in Saint Petersburg later that month.
[src:polish-language/adam-mickiewicz] He would spend most of the next five years in Saint Petersburg and Moscow, except for a notable 1824 to 1825 excursion to Odessa, then on to Crimea.
[src:polish-language/adam-mickiewicz] That visit, from February to November 1825, inspired a notable collection of sonnets (some love sonnets, and a series known as *Crimean Sonnets*, published a year later).
[src:polish-language/adam-mickiewicz] Mickiewicz was welcomed into the leading literary circles of Saint Petersburg and Moscow, where he became a great favourite for his agreeable manners and an extraordinary talent for poetic improvisation.
[src:polish-language/adam-mickiewicz] The year 1828 saw the publication of his poem *Konrad Wallenrod*.
[src:polish-language/adam-mickiewicz] Novosiltsev, who recognized its patriotic and subversive message, which had been missed by the Moscow censors, unsuccessfully attempted to sabotage its publication and to damage Mickiewicz's reputation.
[src:polish-language/adam-mickiewicz] In Moscow, Mickiewicz met the Polish journalist and novelist Henryk Rzewuski and the Polish composer and piano virtuoso Maria Szymanowska, whose daughter, Celina Szymanowska, Mickiewicz would later marry in Paris, France.
[src:polish-language/adam-mickiewicz] He also befriended the great Russian poet Alexander Pushkin and Decembrist leaders including Kondraty Ryleyev.
[src:polish-language/adam-mickiewicz] It was thanks to his friendships with many influential individuals that he was eventually able to obtain a passport and permission to leave Russia for Western Europe.
[src:polish-language/adam-mickiewicz] After serving five years of exile to Russia, Mickiewicz received permission to go abroad in 1829.
[src:polish-language/adam-mickiewicz] On 1 June that year, he arrived in Weimar in Germany.
[src:polish-language/adam-mickiewicz] By 6 June he was in Berlin, where he attended lectures by the philosopher Hegel.
[src:polish-language/adam-mickiewicz] In February 1830 he visited Prague, later returning to Weimar, where he received a cordial reception from the writer and polymath Goethe.
[src:polish-language/adam-mickiewicz] He then continued on through Germany all the way to Italy, which he entered via the Alps' Splügen Pass.
[src:polish-language/adam-mickiewicz] Accompanied by an old friend, the poet Antoni Edward Odyniec, he visited Milan, Venice, Florence and Rome.
[src:polish-language/adam-mickiewicz] In August that same year (1830) he went to Geneva, where he met fellow Polish Bard Zygmunt Krasiński.
[src:polish-language/adam-mickiewicz] During these travels he had a brief romance with Henrietta Ewa Ankwiczówna, but class differences again prevented his marrying his new love.
[src:polish-language/adam-mickiewicz] Finally about October 1830 he took up residence in Rome, which he declared "the most amiable of foreign cities." Soon after, he learned about the outbreak of the November 1830 Uprising in Poland, but he would not leave Rome until the spring of 1831.
[src:polish-language/adam-mickiewicz] On 19 April 1831 Mickiewicz departed Rome, traveling to Geneva and Paris and later, on a false passport, to Germany, via Dresden and Leipzig arriving about 13 August in Poznań (German name: Posen), then part of the Kingdom of Prussia.
[src:polish-language/adam-mickiewicz] It is possible that during these travels he carried communications from the Italian Carbonari to the French underground, and delivered documents or money for the Polish insurgents from the Polish community in Paris, but reliable information on his activities at the time is scarce.
[src:polish-language/adam-mickiewicz] Ultimately he never crossed into Russian Poland, where the Uprising was mainly happening; he stayed in German Poland (historically known to Poles as *Wielkopolska*, or Greater Poland), where he was well received by members of the local Polish nobility.
[src:polish-language/adam-mickiewicz] He had a brief liaison with Konstancja Łubieńska at her family estate in Śmiełów.
[src:polish-language/adam-mickiewicz] Starting in March 1832, Mickiewicz stayed several months in Dresden, in Saxony, where he wrote the third part of his poem *Dziady*.
[src:polish-language/adam-mickiewicz] On 31 July 1832, Mickiewicz arrived in Paris, accompanied by a close friend and fellow ex-Philomath, the future geologist and Chilean educator Ignacy Domeyko.
[src:polish-language/adam-mickiewicz] In Paris, he became active in many Polish émigré groups and published articles in *Pielgrzym Polski* (*The Polish Pilgrim*).
[src:polish-language/adam-mickiewicz] The fall of 1832 saw the publication, in Paris, of the third part of his *Dziady* (smuggled into partitioned Poland), as well as of *The Books of the Polish People and of the Polish Pilgrimage*, which Mickiewicz self-published.
[src:polish-language/adam-mickiewicz] During this time, he made acquaintances with his compatriot the composer Frederic Chopin who would be one of Mickiewicz's closest friends in Paris.
[src:polish-language/adam-mickiewicz] In 1834 he published another masterpiece, his epic poem *Pan Tadeusz*.
[src:polish-language/adam-mickiewicz] On 22 July 1834, in Paris, he married Celina Szymanowska, daughter of composer and concert pianist Maria Agata Szymanowska.
[src:polish-language/adam-mickiewicz] They would have six children (two daughters, Maria and Helena; and four sons, Władysław, Aleksander, Jan and Józef).
[src:polish-language/adam-mickiewicz] Celina later became mentally ill, possibly with a major depressive disorder.
[src:polish-language/adam-mickiewicz] In December 1838, marital problems caused Mickiewicz to attempt suicide.
[src:polish-language/adam-mickiewicz] Mickiewicz and his family lived in relative poverty, their major source of income being occasional publication of his work – not a very profitable endeavor.
[src:polish-language/adam-mickiewicz] They received support from friends and patrons, but not enough to substantially change their situation.
[src:polish-language/adam-mickiewicz] Despite spending most of his remaining years in France, Mickiewicz would never receive French citizenship, nor any support from the French government.
[src:polish-language/adam-mickiewicz] By the late 1830s he was less active as a writer, and also less visible on the Polish émigré political scene.
[src:polish-language/adam-mickiewicz] In 1838 Mickiewicz became professor of Latin literature at the Lausanne Academy, in Switzerland.
[src:polish-language/adam-mickiewicz] His lectures were well received, and in 1840 he was appointed to the newly established chair of Slavic languages and literatures at the Collège de France.
[src:polish-language/adam-mickiewicz] Leaving Lausanne, he was made an honorary Lausanne Academy professor.
[src:polish-language/adam-mickiewicz] Mickiewicz would, however, hold the Collège de France post for little more than three years, his last lecture being delivered on 28 May 1844.
[src:polish-language/adam-mickiewicz] His lectures were popular, drawing many listeners in addition to enrolled students, and receiving reviews in the press.
[src:polish-language/adam-mickiewicz] Over the years he became increasingly possessed by religious mysticism as he fell under the influence of the Polish philosopher Andrzej Towiański, whom he met in 1841.
[src:polish-language/adam-mickiewicz] His lectures became a medley of religion and politics, punctuated by controversial attacks on the Catholic Church, and thus brought him under censure by the French government.
[src:polish-language/adam-mickiewicz] The messianic element conflicted with Roman Catholic teachings, and some of his works were placed on the Church's list of prohibited books, though both Mickiewicz and Towiański regularly attended Catholic mass and encouraged their followers to do so.
[src:polish-language/adam-mickiewicz] In 1846 Mickiewicz severed his ties with Towiański, following the rise of revolutionary sentiment in Europe, manifested in events such as the Kraków Uprising of February 1846.
[src:polish-language/adam-mickiewicz] Mickiewicz criticized Towiański's passivity and returned to the traditional Catholic Church.
[src:polish-language/adam-mickiewicz] In 1847 Mickiewicz befriended American journalist, critic and women's-rights advocate Margaret Fuller.
[src:polish-language/adam-mickiewicz] In March 1848 he was part of a Polish delegation received in audience by Pope Pius IX, whom he asked to support the enslaved nations and the French Revolution of 1848.
[src:polish-language/adam-mickiewicz] Soon after, in April 1848, he organized a military unit, the Mickiewicz Legion, to support the insurgents, hoping to liberate the Polish and other Slavic lands.
[src:polish-language/adam-mickiewicz] The unit never became large enough to be more than symbolic, and in the fall of 1848 Mickiewicz returned to Paris and became more active again on the political scene.
[src:polish-language/adam-mickiewicz] In December 1848 he was offered a post at the Jagiellonian University in Austrian-ruled Kraków, but the offer was soon withdrawn after pressure from Austrian authorities.
[src:polish-language/adam-mickiewicz] In the winter of 1848–49, Polish composer Frédéric Chopin, in the final months of his own life, visited his ailing compatriot soothed the poet's nerves with his piano music.
[src:polish-language/adam-mickiewicz] Over a dozen years earlier, Chopin had set two of Mickiewicz's poems to music (see Polish songs by Frédéric Chopin).
[src:polish-language/adam-mickiewicz] In the winter of 1849 Mickiewicz founded a French-language newspaper, *La Tribune des Peuples* (*The Peoples' Tribune*), supported by a wealthy Polish émigré activist, Ksawery Branicki.
[src:polish-language/adam-mickiewicz] Mickiewicz wrote over 70 articles for the *Tribune* during its short existence: it came out between 15 March and 10 November 1849, when the authorities shut it down.
[src:polish-language/adam-mickiewicz] His articles supported democracy and socialism and many ideals of the French Revolution and of the Napoleonic era, though he held few illusions regarding the idealism of the House of Bonaparte.
[src:polish-language/adam-mickiewicz] He supported the restoration of the French Empire in 1851.
[src:polish-language/adam-mickiewicz] In April 1852 he lost his post at the Collège de France, which he had been allowed to keep up to that point (though without the right to lecture).
[src:polish-language/adam-mickiewicz] On 31 October 1852 he was hired as a librarian at the Bibliothèque de l'Arsenal.
[src:polish-language/adam-mickiewicz] There he was visited by another Polish poet, Cyprian Norwid, who wrote of the meeting in his work *Czarne kwiaty.
[src:polish-language/adam-mickiewicz] Białe kwiaty*; and there Mickiewicz's wife Celina died.
[src:polish-language/adam-mickiewicz] Mickiewicz welcomed the Crimean War of 1853–1856, which he hoped would lead to a new European order including a restored independent Poland.
[src:polish-language/adam-mickiewicz] His last composition, a Latin ode *Ad Napolionem III Caesarem Augustum Ode in Bomersundum captum*, honored Napoleon III and celebrated the British-French victory over Russia at the Battle of Bomarsund in Åland in August 1854.
[src:polish-language/adam-mickiewicz] Polish émigrés associated with the Hôtel Lambert persuaded him to become active again in politics.
[src:polish-language/adam-mickiewicz] Soon after the Crimean War broke out (October 1853), the French government entrusted him with a diplomatic mission.
[src:polish-language/adam-mickiewicz] He left Paris on 11 September 1855, arriving in Constantinople, in the Ottoman Empire, on 22 September.
[src:polish-language/adam-mickiewicz] There, working with Michał Czajkowski (Sadyk Pasha), he began organizing Polish forces to fight under Ottoman command against Russia.
[src:polish-language/adam-mickiewicz] With his friend Armand Lévy he also set about organizing a Jewish legion.
[src:polish-language/adam-mickiewicz] He returned ill from a trip to a military camp to his apartment on Yenişehir Street in the Pera (now Beyoğlu) district of Constantinople and died on 26 November 1855.
[src:polish-language/adam-mickiewicz] Though Tadeusz Boy-Żeleński and others have speculated that political enemies might have poisoned Mickiewicz, there is no proof of this, and he probably contracted cholera, which claimed other lives there at the time.
[src:polish-language/adam-mickiewicz] Mickiewicz's remains were transported to France, boarding ship on 31 December 1855, and were buried at Montmorency, Val-d'Oise, on 21 January 1861.
[src:polish-language/adam-mickiewicz] In 1890 they were disinterred, moved to Austrian Poland, and on 4 July entombed in the Crypts of the Bards of Kraków's Wawel Cathedral, a place of final repose for a number of persons important to Poland's political and cultural history.
[src:polish-language/adam-mickiewicz] Mickiewicz's childhood environment exerted a major influence on his literary work.
[src:polish-language/adam-mickiewicz] The year 1812 also marked his father's death.
[src:polish-language/adam-mickiewicz] Later, the poet's personality and subsequent works were greatly influenced by his four years of living and studying in Vilnius.
[src:polish-language/adam-mickiewicz] His first poems, such as the 1818 *Zima miejska* (*City Winter*) and the 1819 *Kartofla* (*Potato*), were classical in style, influenced by Voltaire.
[src:polish-language/adam-mickiewicz] His *Ballads and Romances* and poetry anthologies published in 1822 (including the opening poem *Romantyczność*, *Romanticism*) and 1823 mark the start of romanticism in Poland.
[src:polish-language/adam-mickiewicz] Mickiewicz's influence popularized the use of folklore, folk literary forms, and historism in Polish romantic literature.
[src:polish-language/adam-mickiewicz] His exile to Moscow exposed him to a cosmopolitan environment, more international than provincial Vilnius and Kaunas in Lithuania.
[src:polish-language/adam-mickiewicz] This period saw a further evolution in his writing style, with *Sonety* (Sonnets, 1826) and *Konrad Wallenrod* (1828), both published in Russia.
[src:polish-language/adam-mickiewicz] The *Sonety*, mainly comprising his *Crimean Sonnets*, highlight the poet's ability and desire to write, and his longing for his homeland.
[src:polish-language/adam-mickiewicz] One of his major works, *Dziady* (Forefathers' Eve), comprises several parts written over an extended period of time.
[src:polish-language/adam-mickiewicz] It began with publication of parts II and IV in 1823.
[src:polish-language/adam-mickiewicz] Miłosz remarks that it was "Mickiewicz's major theatrical achievement", a work which Mickiewicz saw as ongoing and to be continued in further parts.
[src:polish-language/adam-mickiewicz] Its title refers to the pagan ancestor commemoration that had been practiced by Slavic and Baltic peoples on All Souls' Day.
[src:polish-language/adam-mickiewicz] The year 1832 saw the publication of part III: much superior to the earlier parts, a "laboratory of innovative genres, styles and forms".
[src:polish-language/adam-mickiewicz] Part III was largely written over a few days; the "Great Improvisation" section, a "masterpiece of Polish poetry", is said to have been created during a single inspired night.
[src:polish-language/adam-mickiewicz] A long descriptive poem, *Ustęp* (*Digression*), accompanying part III and written sometime before it, sums up Mickiewicz's experiences in, and views on, Russia, portrays it as a huge prison, pities the oppressed Russian people, and wonders about their future.
[src:polish-language/adam-mickiewicz] Miłosz describes it as a "summation of Polish attitudes towards Russia in the nineteenth century" and notes that it inspired responses from Pushkin (*The Bronze Horseman*) and Joseph Conrad (*Under Western Eyes*).
[src:polish-language/adam-mickiewicz] Mickiewicz's *Konrad Wallenrod* (1828), a narrative poem describing battles of the Christian order of Teutonic Knights against the pagans of Lithuania, is a thinly veiled allusion to the long feud between Russia and Poland.
[src:polish-language/adam-mickiewicz] The plot involves the use of subterfuge against a stronger enemy, and the poem analyzes moral dilemmas faced by the Polish insurgents who would soon launch the November 1830 Uprising.
[src:polish-language/adam-mickiewicz] Controversial to an older generation of readers, *Konrad Wallenrod* was seen by the young as a call to arms and was praised as such by an Uprising leader, poet Ludwik Nabielak.
[src:polish-language/adam-mickiewicz] Similarly noteworthy is Mickiewicz's earlier and longer 1823 poem, *Grażyna*, depicting the exploits of a Lithuanian chieftainess against the Teutonic Knights.
[src:polish-language/adam-mickiewicz] Miłosz writes that *Grażyna* "combines a metallic beat of lines and syntactical rigor with a plot and motifs dear to the Romantics." It is said by Christien Ostrowski to have inspired Emilia Plater, a military heroine of the November 1830 Uprising.
[src:polish-language/adam-mickiewicz] A similar message informs Mickiewicz's "*Oda do młodości*" ("Ode to Youth").
[src:polish-language/adam-mickiewicz] He was an authority to the young insurgents of 1830–31, who expected him to participate in the fighting (the poet Maurycy Gosławski wrote a dedicated poem urging him to do so).
[src:polish-language/adam-mickiewicz] Yet it is likely that Mickiewicz was no longer as idealistic and supportive of military action as he had been a few years earlier, and his new works such as *Do Matki Polki* (*To a Polish Mother*, 1830), while still patriotic, also began to reflect on the tragedy of resistance.
[src:polish-language/adam-mickiewicz] His meetings with refugees and escaping insurgents around 1831 resulted in works such as *Reduta Ordona* (*Ordon's Redoubt*), *Nocleg* (*Night Bivouac*) and *Śmierć pułkownika* (*Death of the Colonel*).
[src:polish-language/adam-mickiewicz] Wyka notes the irony that some of the most important literary works about the 1830 Uprising were written by Mickiewicz, who never took part in a battle or even saw a battlefield.
[src:polish-language/adam-mickiewicz] It is followed by a longer "moral catechism" aimed at Polish émigrés.
[src:polish-language/adam-mickiewicz] The book sets out a messianist metaphor of Poland as the "Christ of nations".
[src:polish-language/adam-mickiewicz] Described by Wyka as a propaganda piece, it was relatively simple, using biblical metaphors and the like to reach less-discriminating readers.
[src:polish-language/adam-mickiewicz] It became popular not only among Poles but, in translations, among some other peoples, primarily those which lacked their own sovereign states.
[src:polish-language/adam-mickiewicz] The *Books* were influential in framing Mickiewicz's image among many not as that of a poet and author but as that of ideologue of freedom.
[src:polish-language/adam-mickiewicz] The occasional poems that Mickiewicz wrote in his final decades have been described as "exquisite, gnomic, extremely short and concise".
[src:polish-language/adam-mickiewicz] His *Lausanne Lyrics*, (1839–40) are, writes Miłosz, "untranslatable masterpieces of metaphysical meditation.
[src:polish-language/adam-mickiewicz] In the 1830s (as early as 1830; as late as 1837) he worked on a futurist or science-fiction work, *A History of the Future*.
[src:polish-language/adam-mickiewicz] (*Historia przyszłości*, or *L’histoire d’avenir*) It predicted inventions similar to radio and television, and interplanetary communication using balloons.
[src:polish-language/adam-mickiewicz] Written partially in French, it was never completed and was partly destroyed by the author, but parts of its seven versions survive.
[src:polish-language/adam-mickiewicz] Other French-language works by Mickiewicz include the dramas *Konfederaci barscy* (*The Bar Confederates*) and *Jacques Jasiński, ous les deux Polognes* (*Jacques Jasiński, or the Two Polands*).
[src:polish-language/adam-mickiewicz] These would not achieve much recognition, and would not be published till 1866.
[src:polish-language/adam-mickiewicz] Mickiewicz did not write any poems in Lithuanian.
[src:polish-language/adam-mickiewicz] However, it is known that he did have some understanding of the Lithuanian language, although some Polish commentators describe it as limited.
[src:polish-language/adam-mickiewicz] In the poem *Grażyna*, Mickiewicz quoted one sentence from Kristijonas Donelaitis' Lithuanian-language poem *The Seasons*.
[src:polish-language/adam-mickiewicz] In *Pan Tadeusz*, there is an un-Polonized Lithuanian name Baublys.
[src:polish-language/adam-mickiewicz] Furthermore, due to Mickiewicz's position as lecturer on Lithuanian folklore and mythology in Collège de France, it can be inferred that he must have known the language sufficiently to lecture about it.
[src:polish-language/adam-mickiewicz] It is known that Adam Mickiewicz often sang Lithuanian folk songs with the Samogitian Ludmilew Korylski.
[src:polish-language/adam-mickiewicz] For example, in the early 1850s when in Paris, Mickiewicz interrupted a Lithuanian folk song sung by Ludmilew Korylski, commenting that he was singing it wrong and hence wrote down on a piece of paper how to sing the song correctly.
[src:polish-language/adam-mickiewicz] On the piece of paper, there are fragments of three different Lithuanian folk songs (*Ejk Tatuszeli i bytiu darża*, *Atjo żałnieros par łauka*, *Ej warneli, jod warneli isz*), which are the sole, as of now, known Lithuanian writings by Adam Mickiewicz.
[src:polish-language/adam-mickiewicz] The folk songs are known to have been sung in Darbėnai.
[src:polish-language/adam-mickiewicz] A prime figure of the Polish Romantic period, Mickiewicz is counted as one of Poland's Three Bards (the others being Zygmunt Krasiński and Juliusz Słowacki) and the greatest poet in all Polish literature.
[src:polish-language/adam-mickiewicz] Mickiewicz has long been regarded as Poland's national poet and is a revered figure in Lithuania.
[src:polish-language/adam-mickiewicz] He is also considered one of the greatest Slavic and European poets.
[src:polish-language/adam-mickiewicz] He has been described as a "Slavic bard." He was a leading Romantic dramatist and has been compared in Poland and in Europe with Byron and Goethe.
[src:polish-language/adam-mickiewicz] The works of Mickiewicz also promoted the Lithuanian National Revival and the development of national self-awareness.
[src:polish-language/adam-mickiewicz] Mickiewicz's works began to be translated into the Lithuanian language when he was still alive (e.g.
[src:polish-language/adam-mickiewicz] Moreover, Mickiewicz's works has influenced the pioneers of the Lithuanian National Revival in the 19th century (e.g.
[src:polish-language/adam-mickiewicz] Antanas Baranauskas, Jonas Basanavičius, Stasys Matulaitis, Mykolas Biržiška, Petras Vileišis).
[src:polish-language/adam-mickiewicz] Furthermore, the beginning of Vincas Kudirka's *Tautiška giesmė* (1898), the national anthem of Lithuania since 1919 and since 1988, is a paraphrase of the beginning of a poem *Pan Tadeusz*.
[src:polish-language/adam-mickiewicz] The translation into Lithuanian and publishing of Mickiewicz's works has continued after the restoration of Lithuania's statehood in 1918.
[src:polish-language/adam-mickiewicz] Edward Henry Lewinski Corwin described Mickiewicz's works as Promethean, as "reaching more Polish hearts" than the other Polish Bards, and affirmed Danish critic Georg Brandes' assessment of Mickiewicz's works as "healthier" than those of Byron, Shakespeare, Homer, and Goethe.
[src:polish-language/adam-mickiewicz] He has been a character in works of fiction, including a large body of dramatized biographies, e.g., in 1900, Stanisław Wyspiański's *Legion*.
[src:polish-language/adam-mickiewicz] He has also been a subject of many paintings, by Eugène Delacroix, Józef Oleszkiewicz, Aleksander Orłowski, Wojciech Stattler and Walenty Wańkowicz.
[src:polish-language/adam-mickiewicz] Monuments and other tributes (streets and schools named for him) abound in Poland and Lithuania, and in other former territories of the Polish–Lithuanian Commonwealth: Ukraine and Belarus.
[src:polish-language/adam-mickiewicz] He has also been the subject of many statues and busts by Antoine Bourdelle, David d'Angers, Antoni Kurzawa, Władysław Oleszczyński, Zbigniew Pronaszko, Teodor Rygier, Wacław Szymanowski and Jakub Tatarkiewicz.
[src:polish-language/adam-mickiewicz] In 1898, the 100th anniversary of his birth, a towering statue by Cyprian Godebski was erected in Warsaw.
[src:polish-language/adam-mickiewicz] Its base carries the inscription, "To the Poet from the People." In 1955, the 100th anniversary of his death, the University of Poznań adopted him as its official patron.
[src:polish-language/adam-mickiewicz] Much has been written about Mickiewicz, though the vast majority of this scholarly and popular literature is available only in Polish.
[src:polish-language/adam-mickiewicz] Works devoted to him, according to Koropeckyi, author of a 2008 English biography, "could fill a good shelf or two." Koropeckyi notes that, apart from some specialist literature, only five book-length biographies of Mickiewicz have been published in English.
[src:polish-language/adam-mickiewicz] Mickiewicz is known as a Polish poet, Polish-Lithuanian, Lithuanian, or Belarusian.
[src:polish-language/adam-mickiewicz] Some sources assert that Mickiewicz's mother was descended from a converted, Frankist Jewish family.
[src:polish-language/adam-mickiewicz] Polish historian Kazimierz Wyka, in his biographic entry in *Polski Słownik Biograficzny* (1975) wrote that this hypothesis, based on the fact that his mother's maiden name, Majewska, was popular among Frankist Jews, but has not been proven.
[src:polish-language/adam-mickiewicz] Wyka states that the poet's mother was the daughter of a noble (*szlachta*) family of Starykoń coat of arms, living on an estate at Czombrów in Nowogródek Voivodeship (Navahrudak Voivodeship).
[src:polish-language/adam-mickiewicz] According to the Belarusian historian Rybczonek, Mickiewicz's mother had Tatar (Lipka Tatars) roots.
[src:polish-language/adam-mickiewicz] Virgil Krapauskas noted that "Lithuanians like to prove that Adam Mickiewicz was Lithuanian" while Tomas Venclova described this attitude as "the story of Mickiewicz's appropriation by Lithuanian culture".
[src:polish-language/adam-mickiewicz] Mickiewicz had been brought up in the culture of the Polish–Lithuanian Commonwealth, a multicultural state that had encompassed most of what today are the separate countries of Poland, Lithuania, Belarus and Ukraine.
[src:polish-language/adam-mickiewicz] To Mickiewicz, a splitting of that multicultural state into separate entities – due to trends such as Lithuanian National Revival – was undesirable, if not outright unthinkable.
[src:polish-language/adam-mickiewicz] According to Romanucci-Ross, while Mickiewicz called himself a *Litvin* ("Lithuanian"), in his time the idea of a separate "Lithuanian identity", apart from a "Polish" one, did not exist.
[src:polish-language/adam-mickiewicz] This multicultural aspect is evident in his works: his most famous poetic work, *Pan Tadeusz*, begins with the Polish-language invocation, "Oh Lithuania, my homeland, thou art like health ..." (*"Litwo!
[src:polish-language/adam-mickiewicz] Ojczyzno moja! ty jesteś jak zdrowie ..."*).
[src:polish-language/adam-mickiewicz] It is generally accepted, however, that Mickiewicz, when referring to Lithuania, meant a historical region rather than a linguistic and cultural entity, and he often applied the term "Lithuanian" to the Slavic inhabitants of the Grand Duchy of Lithuania.
[src:polish-language/polish-language] The traditional 32-letter Polish alphabet has nine additions (*ą*, *ć*, *ę*, *ł*, *ń*, *ó*, *ś*, *ź*, *ż*) to the letters of the basic 26-letter Latin alphabet, while removing three (x, q, v).
[src:polish-language/polish-language] Those three letters are at times included in an extended 35-letter alphabet.
[src:polish-language/polish-language] The traditional set comprises 23 consonants and nine written vowels, including two nasal vowels (*ę*, *ą*) denoted by a reversed diacritic hook called an *ogonek*.
[src:polish-language/polish-language] Polish is a synthetic and fusional language which has seven grammatical cases.
[src:polish-language/polish-language] It has fixed penultimate stress and an abundance of palatal consonants.
[src:polish-language/polish-language] Contemporary Polish developed in the 1700s as the successor to the medieval Old Polish (10th–16th centuries) and Middle Polish (16th–18th centuries).
[src:polish-language/polish-language] Among the major languages, it is most closely related to Slovak and Czech but differs in terms of pronunciation and general grammar.
[src:polish-language/polish-language] In addition, Polish was profoundly influenced by Latin and other Romance languages like Italian and French as well as Germanic languages (most notably German), which contributed a large number of loanwords and grammatical structures.
[src:polish-language/polish-language] Extensive usage of nonstandard dialects has also shaped the standard language; many colloquialisms and expressions were directly borrowed from German or Yiddish and subsequently adopted into the vernacular of Polish in everyday use.
[src:polish-language/polish-language] Historically, Polish was a *lingua franca*, important both diplomatically and academically in Central and part of Eastern Europe.
[src:polish-language/polish-language] In addition to being the official language of Poland, Polish is also spoken as a second language in eastern Germany, northern Czech Republic and Slovakia, western parts of Belarus and Ukraine as well as in southeast Lithuania and Latvia.
[src:polish-language/polish-language] Because of the emigration from Poland during different time periods, most notably after World War II, millions of Polish speakers can also be found in countries such as Canada, Argentina, Brazil, Israel, Australia, the United Kingdom and the United States.
[src:polish-language/polish-language] Polish began to emerge as a distinct language around the 10th century, the process largely triggered by the establishment and development of the Polish state.
[src:polish-language/polish-language] At the time, it was a collection of dialect groups with some mutual features, but much regional variation was present.
[src:polish-language/polish-language] Mieszko I, ruler of the Polans tribe from the Greater Poland region, united a few culturally and linguistically related tribes from the basins of the Vistula and Oder before eventually accepting baptism in 966.
[src:polish-language/polish-language] With the arrival of Western Christianity, Poland also adopted the Latin alphabet, which made it possible to write down Polish, which until then had existed only as a spoken language.
[src:polish-language/polish-language] The closest relatives of Polish are the Elbe and Baltic Sea Lechitic dialects (Polabian and Pomeranian varieties).
[src:polish-language/polish-language] All of them, except Kashubian, are extinct.
[src:polish-language/polish-language] The precursor to modern Polish is the Old Polish language.
[src:polish-language/polish-language] Ultimately, Polish descends from the unattested Proto-Slavic language.
[src:polish-language/polish-language] The book is exhibited in the Archdiocesal Museum in Wrocław, and as of 2015 has been added to UNESCO's "Memory of the World" list.
[src:polish-language/polish-language] The medieval recorder of this phrase, the Cistercian monk Peter of the Henryków monastery, noted that "Hoc est in polonico" ("This is in Polish").
[src:polish-language/polish-language] The earliest treatise on Polish orthography was written by Jakub Parkosz around 1470.
[src:polish-language/polish-language] The first printed book in Polish appeared in either 1508 or 1513, while the oldest Polish newspaper was established in 1661.
[src:polish-language/polish-language] Starting in the 1520s, large numbers of books in the Polish language were published, contributing to increased homogeneity of grammar and orthography.
[src:polish-language/polish-language] The writing system achieved its overall form in the 16th century, which is also regarded as the "Golden Age of Polish literature".
[src:polish-language/polish-language] The orthography was modified in the 19th century and in 1936.
[src:polish-language/polish-language] The history of Polish as a language of state governance begins in the 16th century in the Kingdom of Poland.
[src:polish-language/polish-language] Over the later centuries, Polish served as the official language in the Grand Duchy of Lithuania, Congress Poland, the Kingdom of Galicia and Lodomeria, and as the administrative language in the Russian Empire's Western Krai.
[src:polish-language/polish-language] The growth of the Polish–Lithuanian Commonwealth's influence gave Polish the status of *lingua franca* in Central and Eastern Europe.
[src:polish-language/polish-language] The process of standardization began in the 14th century and solidified in the 16th century during the Middle Polish era.
[src:polish-language/polish-language] Standard Polish was based on various dialectal features, with the Greater Poland dialect group serving as the base.
[src:polish-language/polish-language] After World War II, Standard Polish became the most widely spoken variant of Polish across the country, and most dialects stopped being the form of Polish spoken in villages.
[src:polish-language/polish-language] Poland is one of the most linguistically homogeneous European countries; nearly 97% of Poland's citizens declare Polish as their first language.
[src:polish-language/polish-language] Elsewhere, Poles constitute large minorities in areas which were once administered or occupied by Poland, notably in neighboring Lithuania, Belarus, and Ukraine.
[src:polish-language/polish-language] Polish is the most widely used minority language in Lithuania's Vilnius County, by 26% of the population, according to the 2001 census results, as Vilnius was part of Poland from 1922 until 1939.
[src:polish-language/polish-language] Polish is found elsewhere in southeastern Lithuania.
[src:polish-language/polish-language] In Ukraine, it is most common in the western parts of Lviv and Volyn Oblasts, while in West Belarus it is used by the significant Polish minority, especially in the Brest and Grodno regions and in areas along the Lithuanian border.
[src:polish-language/polish-language] There are significant numbers of Polish speakers among Polish emigrants and their descendants in many other countries.
[src:polish-language/polish-language] In the United States, Polish Americans number more than 11 million but most of them cannot speak Polish fluently.
[src:polish-language/polish-language] According to the 2000 United States census, 667,414 Americans of age five years and over reported Polish as the language spoken at home, which is about 1.4% of people who speak languages other than English, 0.25% of the US population, and 6% of the Polish-American population.
[src:polish-language/polish-language] The largest concentrations of Polish speakers reported in the census (over 50%) were found in three states: Illinois (185,749), New York (111,740), and New Jersey (74,663).
[src:polish-language/polish-language] Enough people in these areas speak Polish that PNC Financial Services (which has a large number of branches in all of these areas) offers services available in Polish at all of their cash machines in addition to English and Spanish.
[src:polish-language/polish-language] According to the 2011 census there are now over 500,000 people in England and Wales who consider Polish to be their "main" language.
[src:polish-language/polish-language] In Canada, there is a significant Polish Canadian population: There are 242,885 speakers of Polish according to the 2006 census; in particular, there are concentrations of Polish speakers in Toronto (91,810 speakers) and Montreal.
[src:polish-language/polish-language] The geographical distribution of the Polish language was greatly affected by the territorial changes of Poland immediately after World War II and Polish population transfers (1944–46).
[src:polish-language/polish-language] Poles settled in the "Recovered Territories" in the west and north, which had previously been mostly German-speaking.
[src:polish-language/polish-language] Some Poles remained in the previously Polish-ruled territories in the east that were annexed by the USSR, resulting in the present-day Polish-speaking communities in Lithuania, Belarus, and Ukraine, although many Poles were expelled from those areas to areas within Poland's new borders.
[src:polish-language/polish-language] To the east of Poland, the most significant Polish minority lives in a long strip along either side of the Lithuania-Belarus border.
[src:polish-language/polish-language] Meanwhile, the flight and expulsion of Germans (1944–50), as well as the expulsion of Ukrainians and Operation Vistula, the 1947 migration of Ukrainian minorities in the Recovered Territories in the west of the country, contributed to the country's linguistic homogeneity.
[src:polish-language/polish-language] ), that became part of Poland after World War II.
[src:polish-language/polish-language] Geographical distribution of the Polish language (green) and other Central and Eastern European languages and dialects.
[src:polish-language/polish-language] Polish is not a majority language of any nation outside of Poland, though areas that speak and are majority Polish are present in some neighboring countries.
[src:polish-language/polish-language] The inhabitants of different regions of Poland still speak Polish somewhat differently, although the differences between modern-day vernacular varieties and standard Polish (*język ogólnopolski*) appear relatively slight.
[src:polish-language/polish-language] Most of the middle aged and young speak vernaculars close to standard Polish, while the traditional dialects are preserved among older people in rural areas.
[src:polish-language/polish-language] First-language speakers of Polish have no trouble understanding each other, and non-native speakers may have difficulty recognizing the regional and social differences.
[src:polish-language/polish-language] The modern standard dialect, often termed as "correct Polish", is spoken or at least understood throughout the entire country.
[src:polish-language/polish-language] Silesian and Kashubian, spoken in Upper Silesia and Pomerania respectively, are thought of as either Polish dialects or distinct languages, depending on the criteria used.
[src:polish-language/polish-language] However, it was described by some linguists as lacking most of the linguistic and social determinants of language-hood.
[src:polish-language/polish-language] Many linguistic sources categorize Silesian as a regional language separate from Polish, while some consider Silesian to be a dialect of Polish.
[src:polish-language/polish-language] Many Silesians consider themselves a separate ethnicity and have been advocating for the recognition of Silesian as a regional language in Poland.
[src:polish-language/polish-language] The law recognizing it as such was passed by the Sejm and Senate in April 2024, but was vetoed by President Andrzej Duda in late May 2024.
[src:polish-language/polish-language] According to the last official census in Poland in 2011, over half a million people declared Silesian as their native language.
[src:polish-language/polish-language] Tomasz Kamusella, Agnieszka Pianka, Alfred F.
[src:polish-language/polish-language] Majewicz, Tomasz Wicherkiewicz) assume that extralinguistic criteria decide whether a lect is an independent language or a dialect: speakers of the speech variety or/and political decisions, and this is dynamic (i.e. it changes over time).
[src:polish-language/polish-language] Also, research organizations such as SIL International and resources for the academic field of linguistics such as *Ethnologue*, Linguist List and others, for example the Ministry of Administration and Digitization recognized the Silesian language.
[src:polish-language/polish-language] In July 2007, the Silesian language was recognized by ISO, and was attributed an ISO code of szl.
[src:polish-language/polish-language] The Poznański dialect, spoken in Poznań and to some extent in the whole region of the former Prussian Partition (excluding Upper Silesia), with noticeable German influences.
[src:polish-language/polish-language] In the northern and western (formerly German) regions where Poles from the territories annexed by the Soviet Union resettled after World War II, the older generation speaks a dialect of Polish characteristic of the Kresy that includes a longer pronunciation of vowels.
[src:polish-language/polish-language] Some city dwellers, especially the less affluent population, had their own distinctive dialects – for example, the Warsaw dialect, still spoken by some of the population of Praga on the eastern bank of the Vistula.
[src:polish-language/polish-language] However, these city dialects are now mostly extinct due to assimilation with standard Polish.
[src:polish-language/polish-language] Many Poles living in emigrant communities (for example, in the United States), whose families left Poland just after World War II, retain a number of minor features of Polish vocabulary as spoken in the first half of the 20th century that now sound archaic to contemporary visitors from Poland.
[src:polish-language/polish-language] Polish linguistics has been characterized by a strong strive towards promoting prescriptive ideas of language intervention and usage uniformity, along with normatively oriented notions of language "correctness" (unusual by Western standards).
[src:polish-language/polish-language] Polish has six oral vowels (seven oral vowels in written form), which are all monophthongs, and two nasal vowels.
[src:polish-language/polish-language] The oral vowels are /i/ (spelled *i*), /ɨ/ (spelled *y* and also transcribed as /ɘ/ or /ɪ/), /ɛ/ (spelled *e*), /a/ (spelled *a*), /ɔ/ (spelled *o*) and /u/ (spelled *u* and *ó* as separate letters).
[src:polish-language/polish-language] The nasal vowels are /ɛw̃/ (spelled *ę*) and /ɔw̃/ (spelled *ą*).
[src:polish-language/polish-language] Unlike Czech or Slovak, Polish does not retain phonemic vowel length — the letter *ó*, which formerly represented lengthened /ɔː/ in older forms of the language, is now vestigial and instead corresponds to /u/.
[src:polish-language/polish-language] The Polish consonant system shows more complexity: its characteristic features include the series of affricate and palatal consonants that resulted from four Proto-Slavic palatalizations and two further palatalizations that took place in Polish.
[src:polish-language/polish-language] Neutralization occurs between voiced–voiceless consonant pairs in certain environments, at the end of words (where devoicing occurs) and in certain consonant clusters (where assimilation occurs).
[src:polish-language/polish-language] For details, see *Voicing and devoicing* in the article on Polish phonology.
[src:polish-language/polish-language] Most Polish words are paroxytones (that is, the stress falls on the second-to-last syllable of a polysyllabic word), although there are exceptions.
[src:polish-language/polish-language] Polish permits complex consonant clusters, which historically often arose from the disappearance of yers.
[src:polish-language/polish-language] Polish can have word-initial and word-medial clusters of up to four consonants, whereas word-final clusters can have up to five consonants.
[src:polish-language/polish-language] Examples of such clusters can be found in words such as *bezwzględny*ⓘ [bɛzˈvzɡlɛndnɨ] ('absolute' or 'heartless', 'ruthless'), *źdźbło*ⓘ [ˈʑd͡ʑbwɔ] ('blade of grass'), *wstrząs*ⓘ [ˈfstʂɔw̃s] ('shock'), and *krnąbrność* [ˈkrnɔmbrnɔɕt͡ɕ] ('disobedience').
[src:polish-language/polish-language] A popular Polish tongue-twister (from a verse by Jan Brzechwa) is *W Szczebrzeszynie chrząszcz brzmi w trzcinie*ⓘ [fʂt͡ʂɛbʐɛˈʂɨɲɛ ˈxʂɔw̃ʂt͡ʂ ˈbʐmi fˈtʂt͡ɕiɲɛ] ('In Szczebrzeszyn a beetle buzzes in the reed').
[src:polish-language/polish-language] Unlike languages such as Czech, Polish does not have syllabic consonants – the nucleus of a syllable is always a vowel.
[src:polish-language/polish-language] The consonant /j/ is restricted to positions adjacent to a vowel.
[src:polish-language/polish-language] The predominant stress pattern in Polish is penultimate stress – in a word of more than one syllable, the next-to-last syllable is stressed.
[src:polish-language/polish-language] Alternating preceding syllables carry secondary stress, e.g. in a four-syllable word, where the primary stress is on the third syllable, there will be secondary stress on the first.
[src:polish-language/polish-language] Each vowel represents one syllable, although the letter *i* normally does not represent a vowel when it precedes another vowel (it represents /j/, palatalization of the preceding consonant, or both depending on analysis).
[src:polish-language/polish-language] Also the letters *u* and *i* sometimes represent only semivowels when they follow another vowel, as in *autor* /ˈawtɔr/ ('author'), mostly in loanwords (so not in native *nauka* /naˈu.ka/ 'science, the act of learning', for example, nor in nativized *Mateusz* /maˈte.uʂ/ 'Matthew').
[src:polish-language/polish-language] Some loanwords, particularly from the classical languages, have the stress on the antepenultimate (third-from-last) syllable.
[src:polish-language/polish-language] For example, *fizyka* (/ˈfizɨka/) ('physics') is stressed on the first syllable.
[src:polish-language/polish-language] This may lead to a rare phenomenon of minimal pairs differing only in stress placement, for example *muzyka* /ˈmuzɨka/ 'music' vs.
[src:polish-language/polish-language] *muzyka* /muˈzɨka/ – genitive singular of *muzyk* 'musician'.
[src:polish-language/polish-language] When additional syllables are added to such words through inflection or suffixation, the stress normally becomes regular.
[src:polish-language/polish-language] For example, *uniwersytet* (/uɲiˈvɛrsɨtɛt/, 'university') has irregular stress on the third (or antepenultimate) syllable, but the genitive *uniwersytetu* (/uɲivɛrsɨˈtɛtu/) and derived adjective *uniwersytecki* (/uɲivɛrsɨˈtɛt͡skʲi/) have regular stress on the penultimate syllables.
[src:polish-language/polish-language] Loanwords generally become nativized to have penultimate stress.
[src:polish-language/polish-language] In psycholinguistic experiments, speakers of Polish have been demonstrated to be sensitive to the distinction between regular penultimate and exceptional antepenultimate stress.
[src:polish-language/polish-language] Another class of exceptions is verbs with the conditional endings *-by, -bym, -byśmy*, etc.
[src:polish-language/polish-language] These endings are not counted in determining the position of the stress; for example, ***zro**biłbym* ('I would do') is stressed on the first syllable, and *zro**bi**libyśmy* ('we would do') on the second.
[src:polish-language/polish-language] Reanalysis of the endings as inflections when attached to verbs causes the different colloquial stress patterns.
[src:polish-language/polish-language] These stress patterns are considered part of a "usable" norm of standard Polish - in contrast to the "model" ("high") norm.
[src:polish-language/polish-language] Some common word combinations are stressed as if they were a single word.
[src:polish-language/polish-language] This applies in particular to many combinations of preposition plus a personal pronoun, such as ***do** niej* ('to her'), ***na** nas* ('on us'), *prze**ze** mnie* ('because of me'), all stressed on the bolded syllable.
[src:polish-language/polish-language] The Polish alphabet derives from the Latin script but includes certain additional letters formed using diacritics.
[src:polish-language/polish-language] The Polish alphabet was one of three major forms of Latin-based orthography developed for Western and some South Slavic languages, the others being Czech orthography and Croatian orthography, the last of these being a 19th-century invention trying to make a compromise between the first two.
[src:polish-language/polish-language] Kashubian uses a Polish-based system, Slovak uses a Czech-based system, and Slovene follows the Croatian one; the Sorbian languages blend the Polish and the Czech ones.
[src:polish-language/polish-language] Historically, Poland's once diverse and multi-ethnic population utilized many forms of scripture to write Polish.
[src:polish-language/polish-language] For instance, Lipka Tatars and Muslims inhabiting the eastern parts of the former Polish–Lithuanian Commonwealth wrote Polish in the Arabic alphabet.
[src:polish-language/polish-language] The Cyrillic script is used to a certain extent today by Polish speakers in Western Belarus, especially for religious texts.
[src:polish-language/polish-language] The diacritics used in the Polish alphabet are the *kreska* (graphically similar to the acute accent) over the letters *ć, ń, ó, ś, ź* and through the letter in *ł*; the *kropka* (superior dot) over the letter *ż*, and the *ogonek* ("little tail") under the letters *ą, ę*.
[src:polish-language/polish-language] The letters *q, v, x* are used only in foreign words and names.
[src:polish-language/polish-language] Polish orthography is largely phonemic—there is a consistent correspondence between letters (or digraphs and trigraphs) and phonemes (for exceptions see below).
[src:polish-language/polish-language] The letters of the alphabet and their normal phonemic values are listed in the following table.
[src:polish-language/polish-language] Voiced consonant letters frequently come to represent voiceless sounds (as shown in the tables); this occurs at the end of words and in certain clusters, due to the neutralization mentioned in the *Phonology* section above.
[src:polish-language/polish-language] Occasionally also voiceless consonant letters can represent voiced sounds in clusters.
[src:polish-language/polish-language] The spelling rule for the palatal sounds /ɕ/, /ʑ/, /tɕ/, /dʑ/ and /ɲ/ is as follows: before the vowel *i* the plain letters *s, z, c, dz, n* are used; before other vowels the combinations *si, zi, ci, dzi, ni* are used; when not followed by a vowel the diacritic forms *ś, ź, ć, dź, ń* are used.
[src:polish-language/polish-language] For example, the *s* in *siwy* ("grey-haired"), the *si* in *siarka* ("sulfur") and the *ś* in *święty* ("holy") all represent the sound /ɕ/.
[src:polish-language/polish-language] The exceptions to the above rule are certain loanwords from Latin, Italian, French, Russian or English—where *s* before *i* is pronounced as *s*, e.g.
[src:polish-language/polish-language] *sinus*, *sinologia*, *do re mi fa sol la si do*, *Saint-Simon i saint-simoniści*, *Sierioża*, *Siergiej*, *Singapur*, *singiel*.
[src:polish-language/polish-language] In other loanwords the vowel *i* is changed to *y*, e.g.
[src:polish-language/polish-language] Similar principles apply to /kʲ/, /ɡʲ/, /xʲ/ and /lʲ/, except that these can only occur before vowels, so the spellings are *k, g, (c)h, l* before *i*, and *ki, gi, (c)hi, li* otherwise.
[src:polish-language/polish-language] Most Polish speakers, however, do not consider palatalization of *k, g, (c)h* or *l* as creating new sounds.
[src:polish-language/polish-language] Except in the cases mentioned above, the letter *i* if followed by another vowel in the same word usually represents /j/, yet a palatalization of the previous consonant is always assumed.
[src:polish-language/polish-language] The reverse case, where the consonant remains unpalatalized but is followed by a palatalized consonant, is written by using *j* instead of *i*: for example, *zjeść*, "to eat up".
[src:polish-language/polish-language] The letters *ą* and *ę*, when followed by plosives and affricates, represent an oral vowel followed by a nasal consonant, rather than a nasal vowel.
[src:polish-language/polish-language] For example, *ą* in *dąb* ("oak") is pronounced [ɔm], and *ę* in *tęcza* ("rainbow") is pronounced [ɛn] (the nasal assimilates to the following consonant).
[src:polish-language/polish-language] When followed by *l* or *ł* (for example *przyjęli*, *przyjęły*), *ę* is pronounced as just *e*.
[src:polish-language/polish-language] When *ę* is at the end of the word it is often pronounced as just [ɛ].
[src:polish-language/polish-language] Depending on the word, the phoneme /x/ can be spelt *h* or *ch*, the phoneme /ʐ/ can be spelt *ż* or *rz*, and /u/ can be spelt *u* or *ó*.
[src:polish-language/polish-language] In several cases it determines the meaning, for example: *może* ("maybe") and *morze* ("sea").
[src:polish-language/polish-language] In occasional words, letters that normally form a digraph are pronounced separately.
[src:polish-language/polish-language] For example, *rz* represents /rz/, not /ʐ/, in words like *zamarzać* ("freeze") and in the name **Tarzan**.
[src:polish-language/polish-language] Doubled letters are usually pronounced as a single, lengthened consonant, however, some speakers might pronounce the combination as two separate sounds.
[src:polish-language/polish-language] There are certain clusters where a written consonant would not be pronounced.
[src:polish-language/polish-language] For example, the *ł* in the word *jabłko* ("apple") might be omitted in ordinary speech, leading to the pronunciation *japko*.
[src:polish-language/polish-language] Polish is a highly fusional language with relatively free word order, although the dominant arrangement is subject–verb–object (SVO).
[src:polish-language/polish-language] There are no articles, and subject pronouns are often dropped.
[src:polish-language/polish-language] Nouns belong to one of three genders: masculine, feminine and neuter.
[src:polish-language/polish-language] The masculine gender is also divided into subgenders: animate vs inanimate in the singular, human vs nonhuman in the plural.
[src:polish-language/polish-language] There are seven cases: nominative, genitive, dative, accusative, instrumental, locative and vocative.
[src:polish-language/polish-language] Adjectives agree with nouns in terms of gender, case, and number.
[src:polish-language/polish-language] Attributive adjectives most commonly precede the noun, although in certain cases, especially in fixed phrases (like *język polski*, "Polish (language)"), the noun may come first; the rule of thumb is that generic descriptive adjectives normally precede (e.g.
[src:polish-language/polish-language] *piękny kwiat*, "beautiful flower") while categorizing adjectives often follow the noun (e.g.
[src:polish-language/polish-language] Most short adjectives and their derived adverbs form comparatives and superlatives by inflection (the superlative is formed by prefixing *naj-* to the comparative).
[src:polish-language/polish-language] Verbs are of imperfective or perfective aspect, often occurring in pairs.
[src:polish-language/polish-language] Perfective verbs have a simple future tense (formed like the present tense of imperfective verbs), past tense, subjunctive/conditional, imperatives, infinitive, present gerund and past participle.
[src:polish-language/polish-language] Conjugated verb forms agree with their subject in terms of person, number, and (in the case of past tense and subjunctive/conditional forms) gender.
[src:polish-language/polish-language] Passive-type constructions can be made using the auxiliary *być* or *zostać* ("become") with the passive participle.
[src:polish-language/polish-language] There is also an impersonal construction where the active verb is used (in third person singular) with no subject, but with the reflexive pronoun *się* present to indicate a general, unspecified subject (as in *pije się wódkę* "vodka is being drunk"—note that *wódka* appears in the accusative).
[src:polish-language/polish-language] A similar sentence type in the past tense uses the passive participle with the ending *-o*, as in *widziano ludzi* ("people were seen").
[src:polish-language/polish-language] As in other Slavic languages, there are also subjectless sentences formed using such words as *można* ("it is possible") together with an infinitive.
[src:polish-language/polish-language] Yes–no questions (both direct and indirect) are formed by placing the word *czy* ("whether") at the start, although it's often omitted in casual speech.
[src:polish-language/polish-language] Negation uses the word *nie*, before the verb or other item being negated; *nie* is still added before the verb even if the sentence also contains other negatives such as *nigdy* ("never") or *nic* ("nothing"), effectively creating a double negative.
[src:polish-language/polish-language] Cardinal numbers have a complex system of inflection and agreement.
[src:polish-language/polish-language] Zero and cardinal numbers higher than five (except for those ending with the digit 2, 3 or 4 but not ending with 12, 13 or 14) govern the genitive case rather than the nominative or accusative.
[src:polish-language/polish-language] Special forms of numbers (collective numerals) are used with certain classes of noun, which include *dziecko* ("child") and exclusively plural nouns such as *drzwi* ("door").
[src:polish-language/polish-language] Poland was once a multi-ethnic nation with many minorities that contributed to the Polish language.
[src:polish-language/polish-language] Top right: rope (*sznur* from German *Schnur*).
[src:polish-language/polish-language] Bottom left: shark (*rekin* from French *requin*).
[src:polish-language/polish-language] Polish has, over the centuries, borrowed a number of words from other languages.
[src:polish-language/polish-language] When borrowing, pronunciation was adapted to Polish phonemes and spelling was altered to match Polish orthography.
[src:polish-language/polish-language] In addition, word endings are liberally applied to almost any word to produce verbs, nouns, adjectives, as well as adding the appropriate endings for cases of nouns, adjectives, diminutives, double-diminutives, augmentatives, etc.
[src:polish-language/polish-language] Depending on the historical period, borrowing has proceeded from various languages.
[src:polish-language/polish-language] Notable influences have been Latin (10th–18th centuries), Czech (10th and 14th–15th centuries), Italian (16th–17th centuries), French (17th–19th centuries), German (13–15th and 18th–20th centuries), Hungarian (15th–16th centuries) and Turkish (17th century).
[src:polish-language/polish-language] Currently, English words are the most common imports to Polish.
[src:polish-language/polish-language] The Latin language, for a very long time the only official language of the Polish state, has had a great influence on Polish.
[src:polish-language/polish-language] Many Polish words were direct borrowings or calques (e.g.
[src:polish-language/polish-language] *rzeczpospolita* from *res publica*) from Latin.
[src:polish-language/polish-language] Latin was known to a larger or smaller degree by most of the numerous szlachta in the 16th to 18th centuries (and it continued to be extensively taught at secondary schools until World War II).
[src:polish-language/polish-language] Apart from dozens of loanwords, its influence can also be seen in a number of verbatim Latin phrases in Polish literature (especially from the 19th century and earlier).
[src:polish-language/polish-language] During the 12th and 13th centuries, Mongolian words were brought to the Polish language during wars with the armies of Genghis Khan and his descendants, e.g.
[src:polish-language/polish-language] *dzida* (spear) and *szereg* (a line or row).
[src:polish-language/polish-language] Words from Czech, an important influence during the 10th and 14th–15th centuries include *sejm*, *hańba* and *brama*.
[src:polish-language/polish-language] In 1518, the Polish king Sigismund I the Old married Bona Sforza, the niece of the Holy Roman emperor Maximilian, who introduced Italian cuisine to Poland, especially vegetables.
[src:polish-language/polish-language] Hence, words from Italian include *pomidor* from "pomodoro" (tomato), *kalafior* from "cavolfiore" (cauliflower), and *pomarańcza*, a portmanteau from Italian "pomo" (pome) plus "arancio" (orange).
[src:polish-language/polish-language] A later word of Italian origin is *autostrada* (from Italian "autostrada", highway).
[src:polish-language/polish-language] In the 18th century, with the rising prominence of France in Europe, French supplanted Latin as an important source of words.
[src:polish-language/polish-language] Some French borrowings also date from the Napoleonic era, when the Poles were enthusiastic supporters of Napoleon.
[src:polish-language/polish-language] Some place names have also been adapted from French, such as the Warsaw boroughs of Żoliborz ("joli bord" = beautiful riverside), Marymont ("Marie mont" = Mary's hill) as well as the town of Żyrardów (from the name Girard, with the Polish suffix -ów attached to refer to the founder of the town).
[src:polish-language/polish-language] Many words were borrowed from the German language from the sizable German population in Polish cities during medieval times.
[src:polish-language/polish-language] German words found in the Polish language are often connected with trade, the building industry, civic rights and city life.
[src:polish-language/polish-language] Some words were assimilated verbatim, for example *handel* (trade) and *dach* (roof); others are pronounced similarly, but differ in writing *Schnur*—*sznur* (cord).
[src:polish-language/polish-language] As a result of being neighbors with Germany, Polish has many German expressions which have become literally translated (calques).
[src:polish-language/polish-language] The regional dialects of Upper Silesia and Masuria (Modern Polish East Prussia) have noticeably more German loanwords than other varieties.
[src:polish-language/polish-language] The contacts with Ottoman Turkey in the 17th century brought many new words, some of them still in use, such as: *jar* ("yar" deep valley), *szaszłyk* ("şişlik" shish kebab), *filiżanka* ("fincan" cup), *arbuz* ("karpuz" watermelon), *dywan* ("divan" carpet), etc.
[src:polish-language/polish-language] From the founding of the Kingdom of Poland in 1025 through the early years of the Polish–Lithuanian Commonwealth created in 1569, Poland was the most tolerant country of Jews in Europe.
[src:polish-language/polish-language] Known as the "paradise for the Jews", it became a shelter for persecuted and expelled European Jewish communities and the home to the world's largest Jewish community of the time.
[src:polish-language/polish-language] As a result, many Polish words come from Yiddish, spoken by the large Polish Jewish population that existed until the Holocaust.
[src:polish-language/polish-language] The mountain dialects of the Górale in southern Poland, have quite a number of words borrowed from Hungarian (e.g.
[src:polish-language/polish-language] *baca*, *gazda*, *juhas*, *hejnał*) and Romanian as a result of historical contacts with Hungarian-dominated Slovakia and Wallachian herders who travelled north along the Carpathians.
[src:polish-language/polish-language] Thieves' slang includes such words as *kimać* (to sleep) or *majcher* (knife) of Greek origin, considered then unknown to the outside world.
[src:polish-language/polish-language] In addition, Turkish and Tatar have exerted influence upon the vocabulary of war, names of oriental costumes etc.
[src:polish-language/polish-language] Russian borrowings began to make their way into Polish from the second half of the 19th century on.
[src:polish-language/polish-language] Polish has also received an intensive number of English loanwords, particularly after World War II.
[src:polish-language/polish-language] Recent loanwords come primarily from the English language, mainly those that have Latin or Greek roots, for example *komputer* (computer), *korupcja* (from 'corruption', but sense restricted to 'bribery') etc.
[src:polish-language/polish-language] *auto-moto*), which is not native to Polish but common in English, for example, is also sometimes used.
[src:polish-language/polish-language] When borrowing English words, Polish often changes their spelling.
[src:polish-language/polish-language] For example, Latin suffix '-tio' corresponds to *-cja*.
[src:polish-language/polish-language] To make the word plural, *-cja* becomes *-cje*.
[src:polish-language/polish-language] Examples of this include *inauguracja* (inauguration), *dewastacja* (devastation), *recepcja* (reception), *konurbacja* (conurbation) and *konotacje* (connotations).
[src:polish-language/polish-language] Also, the digraph *qu* becomes *kw* (*kwadrant* = quadrant; *kworum* = quorum).
[src:polish-language/polish-language] The Polish language has influenced others.
[src:polish-language/polish-language] Particular influences appear in other Slavic languages and in German — due to their proximity and shared borders.
[src:polish-language/polish-language] The common Germanic word *quartz* comes from the dialectical Old Polish *kwardy*.
[src:polish-language/polish-language] "Szmata," a Polish, Slovak and Ruthenian word for "mop" or "rag", became part of Yiddish.
[src:polish-language/polish-language] The Polish language exerted significant lexical influence upon Ukrainian, particularly in the fields of abstract and technical terminology; for example, the Ukrainian word панство *panstvo* (country) is derived from Polish *państwo*.
[src:polish-language/polish-language] The Polish influence on Ukrainian is particularly marked on western Ukrainian dialects in western Ukraine, which for centuries was under Polish cultural domination.
[src:polish-language/polish-language] There are a substantial number of Polish words which officially became part of Yiddish, once the main language of European Jews.
[src:polish-language/polish-language] These include basic items, objects or terms such as a bread bun (Polish *bułka*, Yiddish בולקע *bulke*), a fishing rod (*wędka*, ווענטקע *ventke*), an oak (*dąb*, דעמב *demb*), a meadow (*łąka*, לאָנקע *lonke*), a moustache (*wąsy*, וואָנצעס *vontses*) and a bladder (*pęcherz*, פּענכער *penkher*).
[src:polish-language/polish-language] Quite a few culinary loanwords exist in German and in other languages, some of which describe distinctive features of Polish cuisine.
[src:polish-language/polish-language] These include German and English *Quark* from *twaróg* (a kind of fresh cheese) and German *Gurke*, English *gherkin* from *ogórek* (cucumber).
[src:polish-language/polish-language] The word *pierogi* (Polish dumplings) has spread internationally, as well as *pączki* (Polish donuts) and kiełbasa (sausage, e.g.
[src:polish-language/polish-language] As far as *pierogi* concerned, the original Polish word is already in plural (sing.
[src:polish-language/polish-language] *pieróg*, plural *pierogi*; stem *pierog-*, plural ending *-i*; NB.
[src:polish-language/polish-language] *o* becomes *ó* in a closed syllable, like here in singular), yet it is commonly used with the English plural ending *-s* in Canada and United States of America, *pierogis*, thus making it a "double plural".
[src:polish-language/polish-language] A similar situation happened with the Polish loanword from English *czipsy* ("potato chips")—from English *chips* being already plural in the original (*chip* + *-s*), yet it has obtained the Polish plural ending *-y*.
[src:polish-language/polish-language] It is believed that the English word *spruce* was derived from *Prusy*, the Polish name for the region of Prussia.
[src:polish-language/polish-language] It became *spruce* because in Polish, *z Prus*, sounded like "spruce" in English (transl.
[src:polish-language/polish-language] "from Prussia") and was a generic term for commodities brought to England by Hanseatic merchants and because the tree was believed to have come from Polish Ducal Prussia.
[src:polish-language/polish-language] However, it can be argued that the word is actually derived from the Old French term *Pruce*, meaning literally Prussia.
[src:polish-language/polish-language] The Polish language started to be used in literature in the Late Middle Ages.
[src:polish-language/polish-language] Notable works include the *Holy Cross Sermons* (13th/14th century), *Bogurodzica* (15th century) and *Master Polikarp's Dialog with Death* (15th century).
[src:polish-language/polish-language] During the Age of Enlightenment in Poland, Ignacy Krasicki, known as "the Prince of Poets", wrote the first Polish novel called *The Adventures of Mr.
[src:polish-language/polish-language] Nicholas Wisdom* as well as *Fables and Parables*.
[src:polish-language/polish-language] Another significant work form this period is *The Manuscript Found in Saragossa* by Jan Potocki.
[src:polish-language/polish-language] In the Romantic Era, the most celebrated national poets, referred to as the Three Bards, were Adam Mickiewicz (*Pan Tadeusz* and *Dziady*), Juliusz Słowacki (*Balladyna*) and Zygmunt Krasiński (*The Undivine Comedy*).
[src:polish-language/polish-language] Poet and dramatist Cyprian Norwid is regarded by some scholars as the "Fourth Bard".
[src:polish-language/polish-language] The period known as Young Poland produced such renowned literary figures as Stanisław Wyspiański (*The Wedding*), Stefan Żeromski (*Homeless People*, *The Spring to Come*), Władysław Reymont (*The Peasants*) and Leopold Staff.
[src:polish-language/polish-language] The prominent interbellum period authors include Maria Dąbrowska (*Nights and Days*), Stanisław Ignacy Witkiewicz (*Insatiability*), Julian Tuwim, Bruno Schulz, Bolesław Leśmian, Witold Gombrowicz and Zuzanna Ginczanka.
[src:polish-language/polish-language] Five people writing in the Polish language have been awarded the Nobel Prize in Literature: Henryk Sienkiewicz (1905), Władysław Reymont (1924), Czesław Miłosz (1980), Wisława Szymborska (1996) and Olga Tokarczuk (2018).
[src:polish-language/polish-language] Wszyscy ludzie rodzą się wolni i równi pod względem swej godności i swych praw.
[src:polish-language/polish-language] Są oni obdarzeni rozumem i sumieniem i powinni postępować wobec innych w duchu braterstwa.
[src:polish-language/polish-language] All human beings are born free and equal in dignity and rights.
[src:polish-language/polish-language] They are endowed with reason and conscience and should act towards one another in a spirit of brotherhood.
